text=BOOK XXVII. %0a%0aA DESCRIPTION OF PLANTS, AND OF THE REMEDIES DE¬ %0aRIVED FROM THEM. %0a%0aCHAP. 1. (1.)—BESEABCHES OF THE ANCIENTS UPON THIS %0aSUBJECT. %0a%0aThe farther I proceed in this work, the more I am impressed %0awith admiration of the ancients ; and the greater the number %0aof plants that remain to be described, the more I am induced %0ato venerate the zeal displayed by the men of former times in %0atheir researches, and the kindly spirit manifested by them in %0atransmitting to us the results thereof. Indeed their bounteous¬ %0aness in this respect would almost seem to have surpassed the %0amunificent disposition even of Nature herself, if our knowledge %0aof plants had depended solely upon man’s spirit of discovery : %0abut as it is, it is evident beyond all doubt that this knowledge %0ahas emanated from the gods themselves, or, at all events, has %0abeen the result of divine inspiration, even in those cases where %0aman has been instrumental in communicating it to us. In %0aother words, if we must confess the truth—a marvel surpassed %0aby nothing in our daily experience—Nature herself, that %0acommon parent of all things, has at once produced them, and %0ahas discovered to us their properties. %0a%0aWondrous indeed is it, that a Scythian 1 plant should he %0abrought from the shores of the Palus Maeotis, and the euphor¬ %0abia 2 from Mount Atlas and the regions beyond the Pillars of %0aHercules, localities where the operations of Nature have reached %0atheir utmost limit ! That in another direction, the plant %0abritannica 2 * should he conveyed to us from isles of the %0aOcean situate beyond the confines of the earth ! 3 That the %0affithiopis 1 should reach us from a climate scorched by the %0a%0a1 He alludes to the Glycyrrhiza or Scythice, our Liquorice, which is %0astill found on the hanks of the river Volga. See B. xxi. c. 54, B. xxii. %0ac. 11, B. xxv. c. 43, and B. xxvi. cc. 15, 87. %0a%0a2 See B. xxv. c. 38. 2 * See B. xxv. c. 6. %0a%0a3 “ Extra terras.” Meaning, the continental part of the earth. %0a%0a* See o. 3 of this Book. %0a%0a%0a218 %0a%0a%0aPLINY’S NATUUAL HISTOBY. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0aluminaries of heaven! And then, in addition to all this, that %0athere should be a perpetual interchange going on between all %0aparts of the earth, of productions so instrumental to the welfare %0aof mankind ! Results, all of them, ensured to us by the peace %0athat reigns under the majestic sway of the Roman power, a %0apeace which brings in presence of each other, not individuals %0aonly, belonging to lands and nations far separate, hut moun¬ %0atains even, and heights towering above the clouds, their plants %0aand their various productions ! That this great bounteousness %0aof the gods may know no end, is my prayer, a bounteousness %0awhich seems to have granted the Roman sway as a second %0aluminary for the benefit of mankind. %0a%0aCHAP. 2. (2.)—ACONITE, OTHEBW18E CALLED THELYPHONON, CAM- %0aMABON, PABD ALI AN CUES, OB SCOBPIO ; FOUB BEMEDIES. %0a%0aBut who, I say, can sufficiently venerate the zeal and spirit of %0aresearch displayed by the ancients ? It is they who have shown %0aus that aconite is the most prompt of all poisons in its effects %0a—so much so indeed, that female animals, if the sexual parts* %0aare but touched with it, will not survive a single day. With %0athis poison it was that M. Caecilius 6 accused Calpurnius Bestia %0aof killing his wives in their sleep, and this it was that gave %0arise to that fearful peroration of his, denouncing the murderous %0afinger of the accused. 7 According to the fables of mythology, %0athis plant was originally produced from the foam of the dog %0aCerberus, when dragged by Hercules from the Infernal 8 Re¬ %0agions ; for which reason, it is said, it is still so remarkably %0aabundant in the vicinity of Heraclea in Pontus, a spot where %0athe entrance is still pointed out to the shades below. %0a%0aAnd yet, noxious as it is, the ancients have shown us how to %0aemploy aconite for the benefit of mankind, and have taught us %0aas the result of their experience, that, taken in mulled wine, %0ait neutralizes the venom of the scorpion : indeed such is the %0anature of this deadly plant, that it kills man, unless it can find %0a%0a5 See B. xxv. c. 75. %0a%0a6 Properly “ Caelius ”—the same M. Caelius Rufus who is mentioned %0ain B. vii. c. 50. See also B. xxxv. c. 46. %0a%0a7 “ Hinc ilia atrox peroratio ejus in digitum.” Sillig is probably right %0a%0ain his suggestion that the word “ mortiferum ” is wanting at the end of %0athe sentence. Bestia was accused of having killed his wives by the %0acontact of aconite, applied, through the agency of the finger, to the secret %0aparts. 8 See B. vi. c. i. %0a%0a%0aChap. 2.] %0a%0a%0aACONITE. %0a%0a%0a219 %0a%0a%0ain man something else to kill. When such is the case, as %0athough it had discovered in the body a fit rival to contend with, %0athat substance is the sole object of its attack ; finding another %0apoison in the viscera, to it alone it confines its onslaught; %0aand thus, a truly marvellous thing ! two poisons, each of them %0aof a deadly nature, destroy one another within the body, and %0athe man survives. Even more than this, the ancients have %0ahanded down to us remedies employed by the animals them¬ %0aselves, and have shown how that venomous creatures even effect %0atheir own cure. By the contact of aconite the scorpion is %0astruck with torpor, 9 is quite benumbed, assumes a pallid hue, %0aand so confesses itself vanquished. When this is the case, %0awhite hellebore is its great auxiliary: the very touch of it dis- %0apels its torpor, and the aconite is forced to yield before two %0afoes, its own enemy 10 and the common 11 enemy of all. %0a%0aNow, after this, if any one should be of opinion that man %0acould, by any chance or possibility, make such discoveries as %0athese, he must surely be guilty of ingratitude in thus appre¬ %0aciating the beneficence of the gods! In countries frequented %0aby the panther, they rub meat with aconite, and if one of %0athose animals should but taste it, its effects are fatal: indeed %0awere not these means adopted, the country would soon be over¬ %0arun by them. It is for this reason, too, that some persons %0ahave given to hellebore the name of “ pardalianches.” 12 It has %0abeen well ascertained, however, that the panther instantaneously %0arecovers if it can find the opportunity of eating human ordure. 13 %0aSo far as these animals are concerned, who can entertain a %0adoubt that it was chance only that first led them to this dis¬ %0acovery ; and that as often as this happens the discovery is only %0aa mere repetition of the accident, there being neither reason %0anor an appreciation of experience to ensure its transmission %0aamong them ? %0a%0a(3.) It is chance, 14 yes, it is chance that is the Deity who %0ahas made to us these numerous revelations for our practical %0a%0a* See B. xxv. c. 75. %0a%0a10 The hellebore. See B. xxiii. c. 75, and B. xxv. c. 21. %0a%0a11 The scorpion. 12 “ Pard-strangle.” %0a%0a13 See B. viii. c. 41. %0a%0a14 He seems here, by implication, to contradict himself, and, by bis ex¬ %0aplanation, to be sensible that be does so. He would appear not to have %0aknown exactly wbat bis belief was in reference to first causes. %0a%0a%0a220 %0a%0a%0apltni’s natural history. [Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0abenefit ; 15 always understanding that under this name we mean %0aNature, that great parent and mistress of all things : and this %0ais evident, whether we come to the conclusion, that these wild %0abeasts make the discovery from day to day, or that they are %0agifted from the first with these powers of perception. Re. %0agarded in another point of view, it really is a disgrace that %0aall animated beings should have an exact knowledge of what %0ais beneficial to them, with the exception of man ! %0a%0aThe ancients, openly professing their belief that there is no %0aevil without some admixture of good, have asserted that aconite %0ais a remarkably useful ingredient in compositions for the eyes. %0aIt may therefore be permitted me, though I have hitherto %0aomitted a description of the poisonous plants, to point out the %0acharacteristics of aconite, if only that it may be the more %0aeasily detected. Aconite 16 has leaves like those of cyclaminos 1 ’ %0aor of the cucumber, never more than four in number, slightly %0ahairy, and rising from near the root. This root, which is of %0amoderate size, resembles the sea-fish known as the “cam- %0amarus,” 18 a circumstance owing to which the plant has received %0athe name of “ cammaron ” from some; while others, for the %0areason already 19 mentioned, have called it “ thelyphonon.’’ M %0aThe root is slightly curved, like a scorpion’s tail, for which %0areason some persons have given it the name of “scorpio.” %0aOthers, again, have preferred giving it the name of “ myoc- %0atonon,” 21 from the fact that the odour of it kills mice at a %0aconsiderable distance even. %0a%0aThis plant is found growing upon the naked rocks known %0aas “ aconae ;” 22 and hence it is, according to some authorities, %0a%0a15 “ Hoc habet nomen ” is omitted ; for, as Sillig says, it is evidently a %0agloss, which has crept into the text. %0a%0a16 The ancients no doubt knew several plants under the common name %0aof Aconitum. The one here described, is identified by Fee with the Do- %0aronicum pardalianches of Linnaeus, Leopard’s bane. %0a%0a11 See B. xxv. c. 67. Fee says that neither the leaves of the Doronicum, %0anor of any plant of the genus Arnica, bear any resemblance to those of %0athe Cyclamen, or the cucumber. He remarks also, that the contact solely %0aof it is not productive of poisonous effects. %0a%0a18 A kind of crab. 19 At the beginning of this Chapter. %0a%0a20 “ Female-bane,” or “ female-killer.” See B. xx. c. 23. %0a%0a21 “ Mice-killer.” This assertion is incorrect. %0a%0a22 So called from a, “without,” and koviq, “dust.” Theophrastus %0asays that it received its name from the town of Aeon®, in the vicinity of %0awhich it grew in great abundance. %0a%0a%0aChap. 4.] %0a%0a%0aAGERATON. %0a%0a%0a221 %0a%0a%0athat it is called “ aconitum,” there being not so much as dust %0aeven about it to conduce to its nutriment. Such is the reason %0agiven for its name by some : but according to others, it re¬ %0aceives this appellation from the fact that it fatally exercises the %0asame effects upon the body that the whetstone 23 does upon the %0aedge of iron, being no sooner employed than its effects are felt. %0a%0aCHAP. 3. (4.)- A5TH10PIS I FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%0a.Ethiopis 24 is a plant with leaves resembling those of phlo- %0amos,“ large, numerous, hairy, and springing from the root. %0aThe stem is square, rough, similar to that of arction 35 * in ap¬ %0apearance, and with numerous axillary concavities. The seed %0aresembles that of the fitch, being white and twofold ; the roots %0aare several in number, long, fleshy, soft, and of a viscous taste ; %0awhen dry they turn black and hard, and might easily be taken %0afor horns. In addition to ^Ethiopia, this plant grows upon %0aMount Ida in Troas, and in Messenia. The roots are gathered %0ain autumn, and left to dry for some days in the sun, to prevent %0athem from turning mouldy. Taken in white wine they are %0acurative of affections of the uterus, and a decoction of them %0ais administered for sciatica, pleurisy, and eruptions of the %0athroat. The kind, however, which comes from ^Ethiopia, is %0aby far the best, and gives instantaneous relief. %0a%0aCHAP. 4. -AGERATON : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%0aAgeraton 26 is a ferulaceous plant, a couple of palms in height, %0asimilar to origanum 27 in appearance, and bearing flowers like %0aballs of gold. Used as a fumigation, this plant acts as a %0adiuretic; and as a detergent upon the uterus, when used in a %0a. sitting bath more particularly. Its name has been given to it, %0afrom the circumstance that it keeps a very long time without %0afading. %0a%0a25 Also called cikovt]. %0a%0a21 Generally identified with the Salvia argentea of Linnaeus, Silver sage, %0aor else with the Salvia JEthiopis, Woolly sage. It must not be confounded %0awith the plant of the same name mentioned in B. xxiv. c. 102. %0a%0a24 See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a%0a:i * See c. 16 of this Book. %0a%0a26 “Not growing old.’’ It is identified by Fee and Desfontaines with %0a%0athe Acbillaea ageratum of Linnaeus, Sweet milfoil or Maudlin. Littre %0agives as its synonym, the Hypericum origanifolium. • %0a%0a27 See B. xx. c. 67. %0a%0a%0a222 %0a%0a%0aflint's nattjb.il histoby. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 5.—THE ALOE ; TWENTY-NINE KEMEDIE8. %0a%0aThe aloe 28 bears a resemblance to the squill, except that it is %0alarger, and has more substantial leaves, with streaks running %0aobliquely. The stem is tender, red in the middle, and not %0aunlike that of the anthericus. 29 It has a single root, which runs %0astraight downwards, like a stake driven into the ground; its %0asmell is powerful, and it has a bitter taste. The most esteemed %0aaloes are those imported from India, but it grows in the Asiatic %0aprovinces 30 as well. This last kind, however, is never used, %0aexcept that the leaves are applied fresh to wounds; indeed, %0athese leaves, as well as the juice, are glutinous to a marvellous %0adegree, and it is for this property that it is grown in vessels of %0aa conical form, in the same way as the greater aizoiim. 31 Some %0apersons make incisions in the stem to obtain the j uice, before %0athe 6eed is ripe, while others, again, make them in the leaves %0aas well. Tearlike drops are also found adhering to it, which %0aexude spontaneously: hence it is that some recommend that %0athe place should be paved where it is grown, to prevent this %0ajuice from being absorbed. %0a%0aSome authors have stated, that there is found in Judaea, %0abeyond Hierosolyma, a mineral 32 aloe, but that it is inferior to %0athe other kinds, being of a darker colour and more humid than %0aany of the rest. Aloes 53 of the finest quality should be %0aunctuous and shining, of a red colour, brittle, compact, like %0athe substance of liver, and easily liquefied. That which is %0ahard and black should be rejected; the same, too, when it is %0amixed with sand or adulterated with gum and acacia, a fraud %0awhich may be easily detected by the taste. %0a%0aThis plant is of an astringent nature, binding, and slightly %0acalorific. It is employed for numerous purposes, but principally %0aas a purgative, 34 it being almost the only one of all the medica- %0a%0a28 The ancients probably included under this name several distinct species %0aof the aloe. They were well acquainted, Fee says, with the Indian aloe, %0abut probably not with that of Africa. As described by Pliny, he identifies %0ait with the Aloe perfoliata of Linnaeus: Desfontaines gives the Aloe %0aumbellata. 29 See B. xxi. c. 68. 30 “ Asia." %0a%0a31 See B. xxv. c. 102. The aloe is still grown in large wooden vessels, %0ain this country, at least; but only as an ornament. %0a%0a32 He alludes to the bitumen of Judaea, much used by the Egyptians for %0athe purposes of embalmment. %0a%0a33 He is speaking of the prepared aloes of commerce. %0a%0a31 It is still used for this purpose. %0a%0a%0aChap. 5.] %0a%0a%0aTHE ALOE. %0a%0a%0a223 %0a%0a%0araents which produce that effect, that is at the same time a %0agood stomachic, and does not exercise the slightest noxious %0ainfluence upon the stomach. It is taken in doses of one %0adrachma, and, in cases of derangement of the stomach, it is %0aadministered two or three times a day, in the proportion of %0aone spoonful to two cyathi of warm or cold water, at intervals, %0aaccording to the nature of the emergency. As a purgative it %0ais mostly taken in doses of three drachmae; and it operates %0astill more efficaciously, if food is eaten directly afterwards. %0aUsed with astringent wine, it prevents 35 the hair from falling %0aoff, the head being rubbed with it the contrary way of the %0ahair, in the sun. Applied to the temples and forehead with %0arose oil and vinegar, or used as an infusion, in a more diluted %0aform, it allays head-ache. It is generally agreed that it is %0aremedial for all diseases 36 of the eyes, but more particularly for %0aprurigo and scaly eruptions of the eye-lids ; as also for marks %0aand bruises, applied in combination with honey, Pontic honey %0ain particular. %0a%0aIt is employed,also, for affections of the tonsillary glands and %0agums, for all ulcerations of the mouth, and for spitting of %0ablood, if not in excess—the proper dose being one drachma, %0ataken in water or else vinegar. Used by itself, or in combination %0awith vinegar, it arrests haemorrhage, whether proceeding from %0awounds or from other causes. In addition to these properties, it %0ais extremely efficacious for the cure of wounds, producing %0acicatrization very rapidly : it is sprinkled also upon ulcerations %0aof the male organs, and is applied to condylomata and chaps %0aoi the fundament, either in common wine, raisin wine, or by %0aitself in a dry state, according as a mollifying or restrictive %0atreatment is required. It has the effect, also, of gently %0aarresting haemorrhoidal bleeding, when in excess. In cases of %0adysentery, it is used as an injection, and where the digestion %0ais imperfect it is taken shortly after the evening meal. For %0ajaundice, it is administered in doses of three oboli, in %0awater. As a purgative for the bowels, it is taken in pills, with %0aboiled honey or turpentine. It is good also for the removal of %0ahangnails. When employed in ophthalmic preparations, it is %0afirst washed, that the more gravelly portions of it may subside; %0a%0aM There is no foundation, Fee says, for this statement. %0a%0aM It would appear that it is still employed in India for this purpose, %0abut it is no longer used in Europe. %0a%0a%0a224 %0a%0a%0aplint’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0aor else it is put over the fire in a pipkin, and stirred with a %0afeather from time to time, that the w hole of it may be equally %0awarmed. %0a%0a%0aCHAT. 6.—ALCEA : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aAlcea 37 is a plant with leaves, resembling those of vervain," %0aknown also as “ peristereon,” some three or four stems %0acovered with leaves, a flower like that of the rose, and white %0aroots, at most six in number, a cubit in length, and running %0aobliquely. It grows in a soil that is rich without being dry. %0aThe root is given in wine or water, for dysentery, diarrhoea, %0aruptures, and convulsions. %0a%0aCHAP. 7.-THE ALYPON : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aThe alypon 39 has a small stem, with a soft head, and is not %0aunlike beet in appearance. It has an acrid, viscous taste, %0aextremely pungent and burning. Taken in hydromel, with %0aa little sailt, it acts as a purgative. The smallest dose is two %0adrachmae, a moderate dose, four, and the largest, six. When %0aused as a purgative, it is taken in chicken broth. %0a%0aCHAP. 8. -ALSINE, A PLANT USED FOR THE SAME PURPOSES AS %0a%0aHELXINE : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aAlsine, 40 a plant known as “myosoton” 41 to some, grows in the %0awoods, to which fact it is indebted for its name of “ alsine.” 42 %0aIt begins to make its appearance at mid-winter, and withers in %0athe middle of summer. When it first puts forth, the leaves %0abear a strong resemblance to the ears of mice. We shall have %0a%0a37 Identified by Fee with the Malva alcea of Linnaeus, the Vervain %0amallow, an emollient and, comparatively, inert plant. Littre gives as %0aits synonym the Malope malacho'ides, Marsh mallow. Sibthorp identifies %0ait with the Hibiscus trionum, and Anguillara with the Althaea canryibina %0aof Linnaeus. It is probably the same plant as the Alcima, mentioned several %0atimes in B. xxvi. 38 See B. xxv. c. 59. %0a%0a39 Identified with the Globularia alypum of Linnaeus, the Three-toothed %0aleaf Globularia, or Turbith. %0a%0a40 Identified by Sprengel with the Cerastium aquaticum, and by other %0a%0aauthorities with the Alsine media of Linnaeus, the Common chickweed. %0aDesfontaines suggests the Stellaria nemorum, the Broadleaved stitchwort, %0abut Fee prefers the Parietaria Cretica of Linnaeus, Cretan pellitory, as its %0asynonym. 41 “ Mouse-ear.” %0a%0a42 From the Greek akooc, a “ grove.” %0a%0a%0aChap. 10.] %0a%0a%0aANDEOSAMON. %0a%0a%0a225 %0a%0a%0aoccasion, 43 however, to speak of another plant, which may, %0awith much more justice, be called “ myosotis.” As for alsine, it %0awould be the same thing as helxine, 44 were it not that it is smaller %0aand not so hairy. It grows in 45 gardens, and upon walls more %0aparticularly : when rubbed, it emits a smell like that of cucum¬ %0aber. It is used for abscesses, inflammations, and all those pur¬ %0aposes for which helxine is employed ; its properties, however, %0aare not so active. It is applied topically, also, to defluxions of %0athe eyes, and to sores upon the generative organs, and ulcera¬ %0ations, with barley meal. The juice is used as an injection for %0athe ears. %0a%0aCHAP. 9.-THE ANDKOSACES : SIX REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe androsaces 46 is a white plant, bitter, without leaves, and %0abearing arms surmounted with follicules, containing the seed. %0aIt grows in the maritime parts of Syria, more particularly. %0aThis plant is administered for dropsy, in doses of two drachmae, %0apounded or boiled, in either -water, wine, or vinegar: it acts %0amost powerfully as a diuretic. It is used also for gout, either %0ataken internally or used as a liniment. The seed is possessed %0aof similar properties. %0a%0aCHAP. 10.—ANDROSJEMON OE ASCYEON : SIX REMEDIES. %0a%0aAndrossemon 47 or, as some persons call it, “ascyron,” is not %0aunlike hypericon, a plant of which we have spoken already : 48 %0athe stems, however, are larger, redder, and lie more closely %0atogether. The leaves are of a white colour, and like those of %0arue in shape; the seed resembles that of the black poppy, and %0athe upper branches, when bruised, emit a red juice the colour %0aof blood: these branches have also a resinous smell. %0a%0aThis plant grows in vineyards, and it is usually in the middle %0a%0a43 In c. 80 of this Book. %0a%0a44 The Parietaria officinalis; see B. xxii. c. 19. %0a%0a45 He has previously stated that it grows in the woods. The fact is, %0aM. Fraas says, that it grows equally upon garden walls, heaps of rubbish, %0ain plains, upon shady rocks, and upon mountains, below an elevation of %0a1500 feet. %0a%0a46 Generally supposed not to be a vegetable production, but a Madrepore. %0aFee identifies it with the Madrepora acetabulum of Linnaeus. %0a%0a47 “ Man’s blood.” Identified by Sprengel with the Hypericum monta- %0anum, and by Sibtliorp and Fee with the Hypericum perforatum, of Lin¬ %0anaeus, Perforated tutsan or St. John’s wort. 48 See B. xxvi. cc. 53, 54. %0a%0aVOL. V. Q %0a%0a%0a%0a226 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0aof autumn that it is taken up and hung to dry. Used as a %0apurgative, it is bruised with the seed, and taken in the morn¬ %0aing or just after the evening meal, in doses of two drachmae, %0ain hydromel, wine, or pure water, the draught amounting to %0aone sextarius in all. It carries off bile, and is particularly %0agood for sciatica; but in this last case, caper root must be %0ataken with resin the day after, the dose being one drachma, %0ato be repeated every four days : after being purged, it is the %0apractice for the patient, if in robust health, to take wine, but %0aif in a weak state of body, water. It is employed topically, %0aalso, for gout, burns, and wounds, as it tends to arrest the flow %0aof blood. %0a%0aCHAP. 11.-AMBROSIA, BOTRYS, OR ARTEMISIA - . THREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aAmbrosia is a vague name, which has fluctuated between %0avarious plants : there is one, 49 however, which has been more %0aparticularly designated by this appellation, a branchy, shrub¬ %0alike plant, with a thin stem, some three palms in height; the %0aroot of it is one third shorter, and the leaves, towards the lower %0apart of the stem, resemble those of rue. Its diminutive %0abranches bear a seed which hangs down in clusters, and has a %0avinous smell: hence it is that by some persons the plant is %0acalled “ botrys,” 80 while to others it is known as “ artemisia.” %0aThe people of Cappadocia use it for garlands. It is employed %0ain medicine as a resolvent. %0a%0aCHAP. 12.-THE ANONIS OR 0N0NI8 : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe anonis, 81 by some called “ ononis” in preference, is a %0abranchy plant, and similar to fenugreek in appearance, except %0athat it is more shrub-like and more hairy. It has an agreeable %0asmell, and becomes prickly after spring. It is pickled in brine %0afor eating. Applied fresh to ulcers, it cauterizes the margins of %0athem. Tor the cure of tooth-ache, the root is boiled in oxy- %0acrate: taken in drink, with honey, the root expels urinary calculi. %0aFor epilepsy, it is administered in oxyrnel, boiled down to one %0ahalf. %0a%0aCHAP. 13.-THE ANAGYROS OB ACOPON : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe anagyros, known to some by the name of “ aco- %0a%0a49 Identified with the Ambrosia maritima of Linnaeus, the Sea ambrosia. %0a%0a50 The “cluster” plant. It still figures in the Materia Medica. See %0a%0aB. xxv. c. 36, and c. 31 of this Book. ai g ee y X1 j 0t 58 . %0a%0a%0aChap. 15.] %0a%0a%0aAPARINE. %0a%0a%0a227 %0a%0a%0apon,” 62 is a shrub-like plant, with an offensive smell, and a %0ablossom like that of the cabbage. The seed grows in small %0ahornlike pods of considerable length, and resembles a kidney %0ain shape; it hardens about the time of harvest. The leaves of %0athis plant are applied to gatherings, and are attached to the %0aperson in cases of difficult parturition, care being taken to %0aremove them the moment after delivery. In cases where the %0aextraction of the dead foetus is a