ed with it, as already 91 stated. A %0adecoction of it in water is also taken, the following being %0athe method employed in preparing it. Six drachmae of the %0aleaves are boiled, with the branches, in three sextarii of rain %0awater, and the preparation is then left to cool in the open air a %0aday and anight. Salt, too, should be added to it. When old, it %0ais utterly useless. A dilution of wormwood steeped in water %0ais also used, such being the name 92 given to this method of %0apreparing it. This dilution is made by leaving the vessel %0acovered up for three days, any kind of water being used. %0aPounded wormwood is but rarely employed, and the same %0awith the extracted juice of the seed. 93 In cases, however, %0awhere it is extracted, the seed is subjected to pressure as soon %0aas it begins to swell, after which it is soaked for three days %0ain water, if used fresh, and seven, if dry. It is then boiled %0ain a copper vessel, in the proportion of ten heminae to forty- %0afive sextarii of water, after which it is strained off and boiled %0a%0a87 The Artemisia Pontica of Linnaeus, Little wormwood, or Roman %0awormwood. 88 See B. xi. c. 75. %0a%0a89 The Artemisia absinthium of Linnaeus, Common wormwood. %0a%0a90 Upon which occasion a sacrifice was offered on the Alban Mount. %0aSee further as to this Festival, in B. iii. c. 2. %0a%0a91 In B. xiv. c. 19. "Wine of wormwood is still used medicinally. %0a%0a93 “Dilutum.” An infusion. %0a%0a93 It contains a small quantity of essential oil. %0a%0a%0a234 %0a%0a%0aflint’s natural historv. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0agently to the consistency of honey, in the same way as the juice %0ais extracted from the smaller centaury. The juice, however, %0aof wormwood, thus extracted, is bad for the head and stomach; %0awhereas the decoction, on the other hand, is wholesome in the %0ahighest degree, as it acts astringently upon the stomach, carries %0aoff bile, is a powerful diuretic, has a soothing effect upon the %0abowels, and assuages pains in the intestines. With the addi¬ %0ation of sile, 94 Gallic nard, and a little vinegar, it dispels nausea %0aand flatulency, and expels intestinal worms. It removes %0aqualmishness, promotes the digestion, and, with the addition %0aof rue, pepper, and salt, disperses crudities of the stomach. %0a%0aThe ancients were in the habit of giving wormwood as a %0apurgative, the dose being six drachmae of the seed with three %0aof salt and one cyathus of honey, in one sextarius of sea water %0akept for some time. This preparation, however, is rendered %0amore efficacious by doubling the proportion of salt; the seed, %0atoo, must be bruised with the greatest care, as there is con¬ %0asiderable difficulty in pounding it. Some authorities have %0aprescribed the dose above mentioned to be given in polenta, 94 %0awith the addition of pennyroyal; while others recommend %0athe leaves to be given to children in a dried fig, to disguise %0atheir bitterness. Taken with iris, 96 wormwood acts as a %0adetergent upon the thoracic organs: for jaundice it is used %0araw, with parsley or adiantum. 97 In cases of flatulency, it is %0asipped every now and then, warmed in water; for liver com¬ %0aplaints it is taken with Gallic nard, and for diseases of the %0aspleen, with vinegar, pap, 98 or figs. Taken in vinegar it neu¬ %0atralizes the bad effects of fungi and of viscus in wine it is %0aan antidote to the poison of hemlock, and to the bite of the %0ashrew-mouse, and is curative of wounds inflicted by the sea- %0adragon 1 and the scorpion. It contributes also very greatly to %0athe improvement of the sight, and is used as an external appli¬ %0acation, with raisin wine, for defluxions of the eyes, and with %0ahoney, for bruises. %0a%0a94 See B. xx. c. 18. 95 See B. xviii. c. 14. %0a%0a96 See B. xxi. c. 19. 97 See B. xxii. c. 30. %0a%0a93 “ Puls.” See B. xviii. c. 19. %0a%0a99 From a passage in Scribonius Largus, c. 191, it has been concluded %0athat by the word “ visco,”