leaf than the preceding plant, %0aand is not so bitter; it is injurious to the stomach, has a %0alaxative effect upon the bowels, and expels intestinal worms. %0aIt is taken in drink with oil and salt; or else an infusion of it %0ais taken in a pottage made of meal of three-month wheat. %0aWhen employed as a decoction, a handful is used to one sexta- %0arius of water, the mixture being boiled down to one half. %0a%0a2 This, Fee observes, is not the case. %0a%0a3 The Artemisia marilima of Linnaeus, Sea wormwood : see B. xxxii. %0aC. 31. %0a%0a%0a236 pliny’s natural history. [BookXXVIl. %0a%0aC1TAP. 30. (8.)- THE BALLOTES, MELAMPRASION, OR BLACK LEEK: %0a%0aTHREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe Greeks give to the ballotes 1 the other name of “ melam¬ %0aprasion,” meaning “black leek.’’’ It is a branchy plant, with %0ablack angular stems, covered with hairy leaves, larger and darker %0athan those of the leek, 6 and possessed of a powerful smell. The %0aleaves, bruised and applied with salt, are highly efficacious lor %0abites inflicted bv dogs : cooked upon hot ashes and applied in %0aa cabbage leaf, they are curative of condylomata. Mixed with %0ahoney, this plant acts as a detergent upon sordid ulcers. %0a%0aCHAP. 31. -BOTRYS, AMBROSIA, OR ARTEMISIA: ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aBotrys 7 is a shrublike plant, which has small yellow %0abranches, with the seed growing all round them, and leaves %0aresembling 8 those of endive. It is found upon the banks oi %0arunning streams, and is used for the cure of hardness of %0abreathing. The people of Cappadocia call this plant “ am¬ %0abrosia,” others again, “ artemisia.” %0a%0aCHAP. 32. -THE BRABYLA : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aThe brabyla 9 is possessed of astringent properties like those %0aof the quince, but beyond this, authors give no particulars %0arelative to it. %0a%0aCHAP. 33. -BHYON MARITIMUM : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aSea bryon 10 is a plant, no doubt , 11 with leaves like those of %0a%0a4 The Eallota nigra of Linnaeus, the Fetid hallota, or Stinking