A : %0a%0aTWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe other 20 kind of calyx is known by some persons as %0a“ anchusa,” and by others as “ onoclia.” The leaves are like %0athose of the lettuce, but longer, and with a downy surface. %0aThe root is red, and is employed topically, in combination %0awith fine polenta , 21 for the cure of erysipelas: taken inter¬ %0anally with white wine, it is good for affections of the liver. %0a%0aCHAP. 38. -THE CIRCAEA : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe circaea 22 resembles the cultivated trychnon 23 in ap¬ %0apearance. It has a small swarthy flower, a diminutive seed, %0alike millet, growing in small horn-shaped pods, and a root %0ahalf a foot in length, generally triple or fourfold, white, %0aodoriferous, and hot in the mouth. It is found growing upon %0arocks exposed to the sun. An infusion of it is prepared with %0awine, and administered for pains and affections of the uterus: %0ato make it, three ounces of the pounded root should be steeped %0a%0a18 Other readings are “calsa, ” and “calla;” but “calyx” is supported %0aby the text of Dioscorides, B. iv. c. 23. The first kind has been generally %0aidentified with the Arum arisarum of Linnaeus, Hooded arum, or Honk’s %0ahood, and is identical probably with the Aris aros of B. xxiv. c. 94. %0a%0a19 See B. xxiv. c. 93. %0a%0a20 Probably the Anchusa tinctoria of Linnaeus, Dyer’s alkanet. See B. %0axxii. c. 23. %0a%0a21 “ Flore polentae.” See B. xviii. c. 14. %0a%0a22 Sprengel identifies it with the Asclepias nigra, Black swallow-wort, %0a%0abut Fee considers it to be the Circaea Lutetiana of Linnaeus, Parisian %0acircaea, or enchanter’s nightshade. Other authorities have suggested the %0aCapsicum annuum of Linnaeus, Indian or Guinea pepper, and the Celosia %0amargaritacea of Linnaeus, Pearly celosia, or cock's comb. M. Fraas %0asuggests, though with some doubt, the Cynanchum Monspeliacum, the %0aMwitpellier dog’s-bane. 23 gee 3 xx i. c ^5 %0a%0a%0aChap. 40.] %0a%0a%0aTHE CBAT^GONON. %0a%0a%0a239 %0a%0a%0ain three sextarii of wine a day and a night. This potion is %0aeffectual also for bringing away the after-birth. The seed of %0athis plant, taken in wine or hydromel, diminishes the milk in %0anursing women. %0a%0aCHAP. 39.- THE CIBSION : ONE BEMEDY. %0a%0aThe cirsion 24 is a plant consisting of a diminutive and deli¬ %0acate stem, two cubits in height, of a triangular form, and %0acovered with prickly leaves. The prickles on the leaves are %0adowny, and the leaves themselves resemble those of buglos- %0asos 25 in shape, but are smaller, and of a whitish colour. At %0athe summit of the plant there are small purple heads, which %0afall off in the shape of down. This plant or the root of it, %0aworn as an amulet, it is said, is curative of the pains attendant %0aupon varicose veins. %0a%0aCHAP. 40.- THE cuat^gonon; two kinds of it : EIGHT %0a%0aBEJIEDIES. %0a%0aThe crataegonon 20 is similar to an ear of corn in appearance. %0aIt is formed of numerous shoots, springing from a single root, %0aand full of joints. It grows in umbrageous localities, and has %0aa seed like that of millet, with a remarkably acrid taste. If %0aa man and woman, before the evening meal, take three oboli of %0athis seed in three cyathi of water, for forty days consecutively, %0abefore the conception of their issue, it will be sure to be of the %0amale 27 sex, they say. %0a%0aThere is another crataegonon, known also as “ thelygonos,” 2 ® %0aand distinguished from the last mentioned plant by the mild¬ %0aness of the taste. Some persons assert that females, if they %0atake the blossom of this plant in drink, will be sure to con¬ %0aceive before the end of forty days. These plants, used in com¬ %0abination with honey, are curative of black ulcers of a chronic %0anature; they also fill the concavities made by fistulous %0a%0a24 Identified with the Carduus parvifloras of Linnaeus, the Small-flowered %0athistle. 25 See B. xxv. c. 40. %0a%0a26 Identified by Fee and Desfontaines with the Polygonum persicaria of %0aLinnaeus, the Spotted persicaria, red-shanks, fleawort, or lakeweed. Littre %0agives the Crucianella Monspeliaca of Linnaeus, Montpellier petty madder. %0a%0a27 Hence its name, signifying that it strengthens the generative powers. %0a%0aM See B. xxvi. c. 91. %0a%0a%0a%0a240 %0a%0a%0aPLINY’S NATURAL HISTORY. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0aulcers with new flesh, and restore such parts of the body as %0aare wasted by atrophy. They act as a detergent upon purulent %0asores, disperse inflammatory tumours, and alleviate gout and %0aall kind of abscesses, those of the mamillae in particular. %0a%0aUnder the name of “ crataegos ” 29 or %3c%3c cratoegon,” Theo¬ %0aphrastus 30 speaks of the tree known in Italy as the “ aquifolia." %0a%0aCHAP. 41. -THE CROCOD1LEON : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe crocodileon 31 resembles the black chamoeleon 32 in shape: %0athe root is long, of an uniform thickness, and possessed of a %0apungent smell. It is found growing in sandy soils. Taken %0ain drink, it causes a copious discharge of coagulated blood at %0athe nostrils, and in this way, it is said, diminishes the volume %0aof the spleen. %0a%0aCHAP. 42. -THE CYNOSORCHIS OR ORCHIS : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe cynosorchis , 33 by some called “ orchis,” has leaves like 14 %0athose of the olive, soft, three in number, half a foot in length, %0aand lying upon the ground. The root is bulbous, oblong, and %0adivided into two portions , 35 the upper one hard, and the lower %0aone soft. These roots are eaten boiled, like bulbs , 38 and are %0amostly found growing in vineyards. If males eat the upper %0apart, they will be parents of male issue, they .say, and females, %0aif they eat the lower part, of female. In Thessaly, the men %0atake the soft portion in goats’ milk as an aphrodisiac, and the %0ahard part as an antaphrodisiac. Of these parts, the one effec¬ %0atually neutralizes the action of the other . 31 %0a%0a29 See B. xxiv. c. 72. Littre remarks that Pliny is in error here, for %0athat the Cratsegos of Theophrastus is the Cratsegos azarolia of Linnaeus, %0athe Parsley-leaved hawthorn, while the Aquifolia of Pliny is the Holly. %0aAs to the latter point, see B. xvi. cc. 8, 12. %0a%0a30 Hist. Plant. B. iii. c. 15. %0a%0a31 Desfontaines identifies it with the Centaurea crocodileum of Linnaeus, %0a%0aand Littre with the Carduus pycnocephalus of Linnaeus. Ruellius con¬ %0asiders it to be the same plant as the Leucacantha of Dioscorides, which %0aSprengel identifies with the Cnicus Casabonse. Fee expresses himself at %0aa loss as to its identity. 32 See B. xxii. c. 21. %0a%0a33 “ Dog’s testicle.” Considered to be a synonym merely of the Orchis, %0amentioned in B. xxvi. c. 62. 34 This comparison is totally incorrect. %0a%0a35 See B. xxvi. c. 62. 3 « Or onions. %0a%0a31 A tissue of groundless superstitions. %0a%0a%0aChap. 44.] %0a%0a%0aTHE C0CUBALUS. %0a%0a%0a241 %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 43. —THE CHRYSOLACHANUM ; TWO VARIETIES OF IT : %0a%0aTHKEE IiEMEDIES. COAGULCM TERIUS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe chrysolachanum 38 grows in pine plantations, and is %0asimilar to the lettuce in appearance. It heals wounds of the %0asinews, if applied without delay. There is another kind 39 of %0achrysolachanum mentioned, with a golden flower, and a leaf %0alike that of the cabbage : it is boiled and eaten as a laxative %0avegetable. This plant, worn as an amulet by a patient suffer¬ %0aing from jaundice, provided it be always kept in sight, is a cure %0afor that disease, it is said. 1 am not certain whether this is %0aall that might be said about the chrysolachanum, but, at %0aall events, it is all that I have found respecting it; for it is %0aa very general fault on the part of our more recent herbalists, %0ato confine their account of plants to the mere name, with a %0avery meagre description of the peculiar features of the plant, %0a—just as though, forsooth, they were universally known. Thus, %0athey tell us, for instance, that a plant known as “ coagulum 40 %0aterra,” acts astringently upon the bowels, and that it dispels %0astrangury, taken in water or in wflne. %0a%0aCHAI*. 44. —THE CCCUBALTJS, ST RUM US, OR STRYCHNON : SIX %0aREMEDIES. %0a%0aThe leaves of the cucubalus, 41 they tell us, bruised with %0avinegar, are curative of the stings of serpents and of scorpions. %0aSome persons call this plant by the name of “ strumus,” 42 %0awhile others give it the Greek name of “ strychnon its ber¬ %0aries are black. The juice of these berries, administered in %0adoses of one cyathus, in two cyathi of honied wine, is-curative %0aof lumbago ; an infusion of them with rose oil is used for head¬ %0aache, and they are employed as an application for scrofulous %0a6ores. %0a%0aM “ Golden vegetable.” Supposed to be identical with the Atriplex of %0aB. xx. c. 38, our Orage. %0a%0aM Cultivated orage, probably. %0a%0a40 “Earth rennet.” This plant has not been identified. Lobelius lias %0amade a guess at the Serapias ahprtiva of Linnaeus, the Helleborine. It is %0apretty clear that it was unknown to Pliny himself. %0a%0a41 The same, probably, as the Trychnon of B. xxi. cc. 52,105, Solanum %0anigrum or Black nightshade. In the former editions the reading is “cuculus.” %0a%0a42 The “strumous” or “scrofula” plant. %0a%0aVOL. T. %0a%0a%0aU %0a%0a%0a%0a2-12 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 45. —THE CONFERVA : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe conferva 43 is peculiar to running streams, those of the %0aAlpine regions more particularly; receiving its name from %0a“ conferrumino,” 44 to solder together. Properly speaking, it is %0arather a fresh-water sponge than a moss or a plant, being a %0adense, porous mass of filaments. I know an instance where a %0aman, who fell to the ground while lopping a tree of consider¬ %0aable height, and broke nearly every bone of his body, was cured %0aby the agency of this plant. The patient’s body was covered all %0aover with conferva, the application being continually sprinkled %0awith water the moment it began to dry, and only removed for %0athe purpose of changing it when the plant gave signs of losing %0aits virtues. 45 It is hardly credible with what rapidity he re¬ %0acovered. %0a%0aCHAP. 46. (9.)— THE COCCUS CNIDIUS, OR GRAIN OF CNIDOS: TWO %0aREMEDIES. %0a%0aThe Cnidian grain 46 has just the colour of the kermes berry. 4 ’ %0aIt is larger than a peppercorn, and has very heating proper¬ %0aties : hence it is that when used, it is taken in crumb of %0abread, that it may not burn the throat in passing downwards. %0aIt is a sovereign remedy for hemlock, and arrests 48 looseness of %0athe bowels. %0a%0aCHAP. 47. -THE DIPSACOS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe dipsacos 49 has leaves like those of the lettuce, witli %0aprickly tubercles on the middle of the back. The stem of it, %0atwo cubits in length, is bristling all over with prickles of a %0asimilar nature. The joints of the stem are closely covered %0awith two leaves, which form a concave axil in which a saltish %0adew-like liquid collects. 50 At the summit of the stem there %0a%0a43 Possibly the Conferva rivularis, or the C. glomerata of Linnaeus, the %0aRiver conferva or River sponge, or the Green cluster conferva. %0a%0a44 On account of its asserted agglutinative properties. In reality it is %0aan inert plant, and is never used in medicine. %0a%0a45 Fee considers this statement as fabulous in every respect. %0a%0a46 See B. xiii. c. 35. %0a%0a47 “Coccus.” See B. xvi. c. 12. %0a%0a48 This is not the case. Sillig is of opinion that the passage is imperfect. %0a%0a49 The same plant as the Labrum Venereum of B. xxv. c. 108. It is %0aused for carding cloth, but is no longer employed in medicine. %0a%0a60 Hence its name “ Venus’ bath.” %0a%0a%0aChap. 50.] %0a%0a%0aTHE ELATESTE. %0a%0a%0a243 %0a%0a%0aare small heads covered with prickles: it grows in watery %0alocalities. %0a%0aThis plant is used for the cure of chaps of the fundament %0aand of fistula; in which latter case the root is boiled down in %0awine to the consistenc