ised in %0avinegar, and applied topically, are curative of indurations, %0acarcinomata, and scrofulous sores. They disperse also inflam¬ %0amatory tumours and imposthumes of the parotid glands, and %0ait is found a useful plan to foment the parts affected with a %0adecoction of them. Applied with salt, this plant is curative %0aof putrid ulcers and gangrenous sores. %0a%0aCHAP. 58.- THE GLAUX : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aThe glaux 74 was known in ancient times as the “ eugalac- %0aton.” 75 In the leaves it resembles the cytisus and the lentil, %0aonly that they are whiter beneath. The branches, five or six %0ain number, are extremely thin, and, springing from the root, %0acreep upon the ground, with small purple blossoms upon them. %0aThis plant is found in localities near the sea. It is boiled in %0aa pottage made of similago, 76 to increase the milk: females, %0ahowever, after taking it, must immediately use the bath. %0a%0aCHAP. 59. (10.)— GLAUCION : THREE REMEDIES. DIAGLAUCIA : %0a%0aTWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aGlaucion 77 grows in Syria and Parthia; it is a plant of %0astunted growth, and thickly covered with leaves, like those of %0athe poppy in appearance, only smaller and of a more repulsive %0aaspect: it has an offensive smell, and a bitter, astringent taste. %0aThe 6eed, which is of a saffron colour, is put into a vessel %0acoated with potter’s clay, and heated in an oven ; when taken %0aout, a juice 78 is extracted, which is known by the same name as %0athe plant. This juice and the leaves, bruised, are used for de¬ %0afluxions of the eyes, which disappear in an instant, under this %0a%0a74 Fee thinks that it may possibly be the Astragalus glaux of Linnaeus, %0aor Milk vetch, as originally suggested by Clusius. Littre gives as its %0asynonym the Senncbierra coronopus of Poireau. %0a%0a11 The “ Good milk ” plant. %0a%0a16 See B. xviii. cc. 19, 20. %0a%0a77 See B. xx. c. 78, where a similar plant is mentioned. Fee identifies %0athis plant with the Glaucium hybridum, or Chel