epilepsy, fits of trembling, dropsy,vertigo, hardness of %0abreathing, and incipient paralysis. %0a%0aCHAP. 67. (11.) -THE HYPOGLOSSA : ONE BEMEDY. %0a%0aThe hypoglossa 97 is a plant with leaves like those of the %0awild myrtle, of a concave form, prickly, and presenting another %0asmall leaf within, resembling a tongue in shape. A wreath %0amade of these leaves, placed upon the head, alleviates head¬ %0aache. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 68.—HYPECOON. %0a%0aHypecoon 9 * is a plant found growing in corn-fields, with %0aloaves like those of rue. Its properties are similar to those of %0ajuice of poppies. %0a%0aCHAT. 69. —THE IDA2A HEBBA, OB PLANT OF IDA : FOUB EEMF.DIES. %0a%0aThe Idaean" plant has leaves like those of the oxymyrsine ; l %0ato which leaves a sort of tendril adheres, that bears a flower. %0aThis plant arrests diarrhoea, the catamenia, when in excess, %0aand all kinds of haemorrhage. It is of an astringent and %0arepercussive nature. %0a%0aCnAP. 70.- THE ISOPYBON OB PHASIOLON : TWO BEMEDIES. %0a%0aThe isopyron 2 is called “ phasiolon” by some, from the cir¬ %0acumstance that the leaf of it, which resembles that of anise, %0aassumes a spiral form like the tendrils of the phasiolus. 3 At %0a%0asynonym the Centaurea spinosa, Prickly centaury ; in accordance with the %0aopinion of M. Fraas, who admits, however, that the statement that it has %0aneither stem nor flower, would hardly seem to indicate a species of centaury. %0a*• The Ruscus hypoglossum of Linnteus, the Double tongue. %0a%0a98 The Hypecoiim procuinbens of Liunams, Horned cummin. %0am Fee thinks that “ Idaea herba,” “ plant of Ida,” may possibly be one %0aof the synonyms of the Alexandrian laurel. See B. xv. c. 39. Should %0athat identity not hold good, he prefers the Uvularia amplexifolia of Linnmus. %0a%0a1 See B. xv. cc. 7, 37, and B. xxiii. c. 83. %0a%0a1 Fee suggests the Corydalis claviculata of Decandolle. Littrd mentions %0athe Fumaria capreolata of Linnaeus. %0a%0a3 Or kidney-bean. See B. xxiv. c. 40