%0ajuice, the properties of which are, however, very different. It is a plant %0aof an energetic and even dangerous nature, and must never be mistaken %0afor the real caper. %0a%0a7 Mostly thought to be the same plant as the Leontopodium of B. xxvi. c. %0a34. Littre, however, identifies it with the Evax pygmaeus of Linnaeus. %0a%0as Probably the Eehium Italicum of Linnaeus, Italian viper’s tongue. %0a%0a9 There is no resemblance between the Eehium and the lettuce. “ %0a%0a%0aChap. 74.] %0a%0a%0aTHE LITHOSPERMUM. %0a%0a%0a253 %0a%0a%0acubit in length; the flower is diminutive, and of a purple colour ; %0ait grows in champaign localities. In combination with barley- %0ameal, it is used as an application for erysipelas : the juice of %0ait, mixed with warm water, is employed as a sudorific, in %0afevers. %0a%0aCRAP. 74. -THE LITHOSPERMUM, EXONYCHON, DIOSPYRON, OR %0a%0aHERACLEOS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aAmong all the plants, however, there is none of a more %0amarvellous nature than the lithospermum, 10 sometimes called %0a“exonychon,” “ diospyron,” 11 or “heracleos.” It is about five %0ainches in height, with leaves twice the size of those of rue, and %0asmall ligneous branches, about the thickness of a rush. It %0abears close to the leaves a sort of fine beard or spike, standing %0aby itself, on the extremity of which there are small white stones, %0aas round as a pearl, about the size of a chick-pea, and as hard as %0aa pebble. These stones, 12 at the part where they adhere to %0athe stalk, have a small cavity, and contain a seed within. %0a%0aThis plant is found in Italy, no doubt, but that of Crete is %0athe most esteemed. Among all the plants, there is none that %0aI ever contemplated with greater admiration than this; so %0abeauteous is the conformation, that it might be fancied that the %0ahand of an artist 13 had arranged a row of lustrous pearls alter¬ %0anately among the leaves ; so exquisite too the nicety in thus %0amaking a stone to grow upon a plant! The authorities say %0athat this is a creeping plant, and that it lies upon the ground ; %0abut for my own part, I have only seen it when plucked, and %0anot while growing. It is well known that these small stones, %0ataken in doses of one drachma, in white wine, break and %0aexpel urinary calculi, 14 and are curative of strangury. In¬ %0adeed, there is no plant that so instantaneously proclaims, at %0a%0a10 Identified by Fee and Desfontaines with the Lithospermum officinale %0aof Linnaeus, Gremil, gromwell, or stone-crop. Littre mentions the Lithos- %0apermum tenuifiorum of Linnaeus. %0a%0a11 “Jove’s wheat,” or the “plant of Hercules.” %0a%0a12 This description applies to the variety of Gremil, known as the Coix %0alacryma of Linnaeus, Job’s tears, originally an Indian plant; but it may %0ahave been known in Italy in Pliny’s time. %0a%0a11 A poor compliment to Nature, as Fee remarks. %0a%0a14 It has in reality no medicinal properties to speak of; but its name, %0a“stone seed,” and its appearance, would, of course, ensure its reputation as %0aan efficient cure for calculus. %0a%0a%0a%0a254 %0a%0a%0apliny’s NATURAL HISTORY. [Book XXY1I. %0a%0a%0athe mere sight of it, the medicinal purposes for which it was %0aoriginally intended; the appearunce of it, too, is such, that %0ait can be immediately recognized, without the necessity of %0ahaving recourse to any botanical authority. %0a%0aCHAP. 75.-LAPIDIS MUSCUS, OR STONE MOSS : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aThere grows near running streams, a dry, white moss,' 6 upon %0aordinary stones. One of these stones, with the addition of %0ahuman saliva, is rubbed against another; after which the %0afirst stone is used for touching impetigo, 16 the party so doing %0auttering these words :— %0a%0a%3cbsiiyeri xavdapids?, "kvxog uypiog cu/ia diuxa. %0a%0a“ Cantliarides 17 begone, a wild wolf seeks your blood .” 16 %0a%0aCHAP. 76. -THE L1MEUM : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aLimeum 19 is the name given by the Gauls to a plant, in a %0apreparation of which, known to