mpanula laciniata; and other authorities the %0aMichauxia campanuloi'des. %0a%0aM See B. xx. c: 32. %0a%0a10 “Mouse-ears.” Fee identifies it with the .Myosotis scorpioides of %0a%0a%0a256 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0afrom a single root numerous hollowed stems, of a somewhat %0areddish colour; and bearing at the lower extremities swarthy, %0anarrow, oblong leaves, sharp on the back, arranged in pairs %0aat regular distances, and springing from delicate branches %0aattached with axils to the main stems. The flower is blue, %0aand the root, a finger in length, is provided with numerous %0afilaments like hairs. This plant possesses certain septic and ul¬ %0acerating properties, and hence is used for the cure of fistula %0aof the eye. The Egyptians say that if upon the morning of %0athe twenty-eight day of their month Thoth, a day which gene¬ %0arally falls in our month of August, a person rubs himself with %0athe juice of this plant before speaking to any one, he will be %0asure to have no diseases of the eyes all that year. %0a%0aCHAP. 81. -THE MYAGROS: ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aThe myagros 31 is a ferulaceous plant, with leaves like those %0aof madder: the seed is of an oily nature—indeed, an oil is %0aextracted from it. Ulcerations of the mouth are cured by %0arubbing them with the juice of this plant. %0a%0aCHAP. 82. -THE NYMA : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aThe plant called “ nyma” 32 bears three long leaves, like %0athose of eudive: applied to scars, it restores the Skin to its %0anatural colour. %0a%0aCHAP. 83. -THE NATRIX : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0a“ Matrix ” 33 is the name of a plant, the root of which, when %0ataken out of the ground, has just the rank smell of the he-goat. %0aIt is used in Picenum for the purpose of keeping away from %0afemales what with a singular credulity they call by the name %0aof “ Fatui.” 34 For my own part, however, I should think that %0a%0aLinnaeus, Scorpion-grass, or mouse-ear, which is not of a corrosive nature, as %0aPliny says, but emollient and soothing. Littre names the Asperugo pro- %0acumbens of Linnaeus, Wild bugloss, German madwort, or great goose-grass. %0a%0a31 Sprengel identifies it with the Alyssum sativum, the Garden madwort; %0aFee with the Camelina sativa of Crantz, the Cultivated cameline. Littre %0agives the Neslia paniculata as its synonym. %0a%0a32 Or “ Nigina,” in some editions. It is utterly unknown. %0a%0a33 Possibly a fabulous plant; though it is generally identified with the %0aOnonis natrix of Linnaeus. Poinsinet de Sivry derives its name from the %0aCelto-Germanic words, nat, “night,” and r«, “wand;” a name given to it, %0aaccording to him, for its efficacy in dispelling the illusions of the night. %0a%0a34 Or “ Fauni,” the same as our nightmare. %0a%0a%0aChap. 86.] %0a%0a%0aTHE ONOSMA. %0a%0a%0a257 %0a%0a%0apersons requiring to be treated with such medicaments as %0athese, must be labouring under a sort of mental hallucination. %0a%0aCHAP. 84. -ODONTITIS : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aOdontitis 86 is a sort of hay-grass, 36 which throws out from a %0asingle root numerous, small, jointed stems, of a triangular form %0aand of a swarthy hue. At the joints there-are small leaves, %0asomewhat longer than those of the polygonos ; 37 and in the %0aaxils formed by these leaves is the seed, similar to barley in %0aappearance. It has a purple, diminutive flower, and is found %0agrowing in meadows. 38 A handful of the stems, boiled in %0aastringent wine, is used for the cure of tooth-ache, 39 the de¬ %0acoction being retained for some time in the mouth. %0a%0aCHAP. 85. -THE OTIIONNA : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aThe othonna 40 is a Syrian plant, resembling rocket in ap¬ %0apearance ; its leaves are pierced with numerous holes, and its %0atlower resembles that of saffron, for which reason some persons %0ahave given it the name of “ anemone.” The juice of this %0aplant is employed in ophthalmic preparations; it is slightly %0apungent, of a warming nature, and astringent as it dries. It %0aacts us a detergent upon cicatrizations, films on the eyes, and %0aall impediments of the sight. Some say that the plant is %0awashed and dried, and then divided into lozenges. %0a%0aCHAP. 86.-THE ONOSMA : ONE PROPERTY. %0a%0aThe onosma 41 has leaves some four fingers in length, lying %0aupon the ground, and indented like those of the anchusa : 42 it %0ahas neither 43 stem, blossom, nor seed. A pregnant woman, they %0asay, if she eats of this plant, or even walks over it, will be sure %0ato miscarry. %0a%0a35 Probably tb’e Euphrasia odontites of Linnaeus, the Red eye-bright. %0a%0a34 “ Inter feni genera.” %0a%0a31 See c. 91 of this Book. There is no resemblance between them. %0a%0a38 On the contrary, it grows in arid, sterile spots. %0a%0a39 Hence its name “odontitis,” “tooth-wort.” %0a%0a10 Its synonym is unknown. Sprengel has identified it with the Tageti s %0apatula of Linnaeus, but that is purely an American plant! %0a%0a41 Probably one of the Borragineae, Fee thinks, but beyond that be %0aconsiders it impossible to say. Desfontaines identifies it with the Onosma . %0aechioides of Linnaeus, the Hairy onosma. %0a%0a42 See B. xxii. c. 23. %0a%0a43 If it is the plant above-mentioned, this is incorrect. %0a%0aVOL. V. %0a%0a%0as %0a%0a%0a258 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural histort. [Book XXYI1. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 87. -THE ONOPORDON : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe onopordon, 44 it is said, has strongly carminative effects %0aupon asses, when they eat of it. It acts as a diuretic and as an %0aemmenagogue, arrests diarrhoea, and disperses abscesses and %0asuppurations. %0a%0aCHAP. 88.-THE OSYRIS : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe osyris 45 bears small, swarthy, flexible branches, covered %0awith dark leaves like those of flax. The seed, which grows %0aupon the branches, is black at first, but afterwards changes its %0acolour and turns red. Cosmetics 4 ® for females are prepared %0afrom these branches. A decoction of the roots, taken in drink, %0ais curative of jaundice. The roots, cut in pieces before the %0a6eed ripens, and dried in the sun, act astringently upon the %0abowels: gathered after the seed has ripened, and boiled in %0apottage, they are curative of defluxions of the abdomen : they %0aare taken also by themselves, bruised in rain water. %0a%0aCHAP. 89. -THE OXYS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe oxys 41 is a plant with three leaves; it is given for %0aderangement of the stomach, and patients eat it who are %0asuffering from intestinal hernia. 48 %0a%0aCHAP. 90. -^THE POLYANTHEMUM OR RATRACHION : THREE %0a%0aREMEDIES. %0a%0aThe polyanthemum, 49 by some persons called “ batrachion,”* %0aby virtue of its caustic properties has an excoriating effect %0aupon scars, and restores the skin to its proper colour. It heals %0awhite morphew 91 also. %0a%0a44 Fee suggests that it may be identical with the Onopyxos of B. xxi. %0ac. 56. Desfontaines, also, identifies it with the Onopordon acanthium of %0aLinnaeus, the Cotton thistle or woolly thistle. %0a%0a45 Probably the Osyris alba of Linnaeus, the Poet’s cassia. Anguillara %0aand Dodonaeus have mentioned the Cbenopodium scoparia of Linmeus, the %0aSummer cypress, or line-leaved goosefoot, but without any good reason, it %0ais thought. Holland calls it “ toad-flax.” %0a%0a46 “ Smegmata.” %0a%0a47 The “sour” plant. Mostly identified with the Oxalis acetosella of %0aLinnaeus, Cuckoo’s meat, three leaved sorrel, or wood-sorrel. %0a%0a48 “ Enterocele.” %0a%0a44 The “many-flowered” plant. Probably the Ranunculus polyanthemos %0aof Linnaeus. See B. xxv. c. 109. %0a%0a50 The “ frog ” plant. %0a%0a%0a51 “ Yitiligines.' %0a%0a%0aChap. 91.] %0a%0a%0aTHE POLYGONOS. %0a%0a%0a259 %0a%0aCHAP. 91. -TI1E rOLTGONOS, POLYGONATOS, TEUTHALIS, CARCI- %0a%0aNETURON, CLEM A, OR MYRTOPETALOS, OTHERWISE KNOWN AS %0a%0a8ANGUINAR1A OR ORIOS : FOUR VARIETIES OF IT : FORTY %0a%0aREMEDIES. %0a%0aThe Greeks give the name of “ polygonos” 52 to the plant %0aknown to us as “ sanguinaria.” 53 It is but little elevated above, %0athe ground, has leaves like those of rue, and resembles grass %0ain appearance. The juice of it, injected into the nostrils, %0aarrests haemorrhage : taken with wine, it has a similar effect %0aupon bleeding at any other part of the body, as also spitting %0aof blood. Those who distinguish several kinds of polygonos, %0amake this to be the male 54 plant, and say that it is so called %0afrom the large number of seeds, or else from its numerous %0abranches. Some call-it “ polygonatos,” 55 from the number of %0aits joints, others, again, “ teuthalis,” and others, “ carcine- %0athron,” “ clema,” or “ myrtopetalos.” %0a%0aThere are some authorities to be found, however, who say that %0athis is the female plant, and that the male is more diminutive, %0aless swarthy, and more jointed, with a seed protruding beneath %0aall the leaves. However this may be, these plants are of an %0aastringent, cooling nature. The seed is laxative, and, taken in %0alarge doses, acts as a diuretic, and arrests defluxions; indeed, %0aif there is no defluxion, it is of no use taking it. Tor burning %0aheats of the stomach, the leaves are applied topically ; and they %0aare used, in the form of a liniment, for pains in the bladder, and %0afor erysipelas. The juice is used as an injection for suppurations %0aof the ears, and by itself, for pains in the eyes. It is admi¬ %0anistered, also, in fevers, tertian and quartan fevers more par¬ %0aticularly, in doses of two cyathi, just before the paroxysms %0acome ou; as also in cases of cholera, dysentery, and derange¬ %0ament of the stomach. %0a%0aThere is a third kind, which grows on the mountains, and is %0aknown as “orios,” 66 similar to a delicate reed in appearance, and %0a%0a52 “ Many-seeded.” 53 “ Blood plant.” %0a%0a54 Identified by Fee with the Polygonum aviculare of Linnaeus, the %0aKnot-grass. %0a%0aw “Many-knotted.” Scribonius says that it received its name, “poly¬ %0agonos,” from its being found everywhere. %0a%0a56 Or “ mountain ” plant. Fee considers it to be the same as the %0asecond kind above mentioned, and to correspond with the female Polygonos %0aof Dioscorides. He identifies it with the Hippuris vulgaris of Linnaeus, %0a%0as 2 %0a%0a%0a260 %0a%0a%0aPLINY’S natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0ahaving but a single stem, with numerous joints running into %0aone another; the leaves of it are similar to those of the pitch- %0atree, and the root is never used. This variety, however, is not %0aso efficacious as those already mentioned, and, indeed, is used %0aexclusively for sciatica. A fourth kind is known as the wild 17 %0apolygonos : it is a shrub, almost a tree in fact, with a ligneous %0aroot, a red trunk like that of the cedar, and branches resem¬ %0abling those of spartum, 58 a couple of palms in length, and with %0athree or four dark-coloured, knotted joints. This kind, also, is %0aof an astringent nature, and has a flavour like that of the %0aquince. It is either boiled down in water to one third, or else %0adried and powdered for sprinkling upon ulceratioriB of the %0amouth and excoriations: it is chewed, also, for affections of %0athe gums. It arrests the progress of corrosive ulcers and of all %0asores of a serpiginous nature, or which cicatrize with difficulty, %0aand is particularly useful for ulcerations caused by Bnow. %0aHerbalists employ it also for quinzy, and use it as a chaplet for %0ahead-ache; for defluxions of the eyes, they put it round the %0aneck. %0a%0aIn cases of tertian fever, some persons pull it up wuth the %0aleft hand, and attach it as an amulet to the body; the same, %0atoo, in cases of haemorrhage. There is no plant that is more %0agenerally kept by them in a dry state than the polygonos. %0a%0achap. 92. —the pancratium: twelve remedies. %0a%0aThe pancratium is called by some the “little squill,” M in %0apreference : it has leaves like those of the white lily, but %0alonger and thicker, and a root composed of a large, red, bulb. %0aThe juice of it, taken with meal of fltches, relaxes the bowels, %0aand acts as a detergent upon ulcers : for dropsy, and diseases %0aof the spleen, it is administered with honey. Some persons %0aboil it till the water becomes sweet; the water is then poured %0aoff, and the root is pounded and divided into tablets, which %0a%0aMare’s tail, or female horse-tail; Littre gives the Equisetum pallidum of %0aBory as its synonym. %0a%0a57 Identified by Fee with the Ephedra distachya of Linnaeus, the Great %0ashrubby horsetail. %0a%0a58 See B, xix. c. 7. %0a%0a53 “ Scillam pusillam.” Fee considers it to be a squill, the variety with %0athe red root of the Scilla maritima of Linnaeus, the Sea-squill. Littre %0agives as its synonym the Pancratium maritimum of Linnaeus, the Seu- %0adaflbdil. %0a%0a%0aChap. 94.] %0a%0a%0aTHE PEKICLYMENOS. %0a%0a%0a2G1 %0a%0a%0aare dried in the sun and used for ulcerations of the head, and %0aother affections which require detergents. It is sometimes %0agiven for cough, a pinch in three fingers in wine, and, in the %0aform of an electuary, for pains in the side or peripneumony. %0a%0aIt is administered, also, in wine, for sciatica, griping pains %0ain the bowels, and retardations of the catamenia. %0a%0aCBAP. 93. —THE PEPLIS, SYCE, MECONIOH, OR MECON APHRODES: %0a%0aTHREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe peplis , 60 known by the various names of “ syce ,” 0 %0a“ meconion,” and “ mecon aphrodes,” is a shrub- like plant, %0aspringing from a single, diminutive, root. The leaves of it %0aresemble those of rue, but are a little larger; the seed, which %0alies beneath the leaves, is round, and smaller than that of the %0awhite poppy. It is ordinarily gathered in vineyards, at %0aharvest-time, and is dried with the seed on, receivers being %0aplaced beneath to catch it as it falls. This seed, taken in drink, %0apurges the bowels, and carries off bile andpituitous secretions: %0aone acetabulum, taken in three heminae of hydromel, is a %0amiddling dose. It is sprinkled also upon meat and other articles %0aof food, as a laxative medicine. %0a%0aCHAP. 94. —THE PE1UCLYMEN0S : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe periclymenos 62 is also a shrub-like plant, with two %0awhitish, soft, leaves, arranged at intervals. At the extremity, %0aamong the leaves, is the seed, hard, and very difficult to %0apluck. It grows in ploughed fields and hedges, entwining %0aaround every object from which it can gain support. The seed %0ais dried in the shade, pounded, and divided into lozenges. %0aThese lozenges are left to dissolve, in three cyathi of white %0awine, fora period of thirty days, and are given for diseases of %0athe spleen ; the volume of which is gradually diminished either %0aby discharges of bloody urine, or else by alvine evacuation, %0athe effects of the medicament being perceptible at the end of %0aten days. The leaves, boiled, act as a diuretic, and are useful %0afor hardness of breathing. Taken in drink, in manner above- %0a%0a40 Probably the Euphorbia peplis of Linnaeus; see B. xx. c. 81. It is a %0astrong purgative. %0a%0a““Fig-plant,” “poppy-juice,” and “ poppy-froth.” In reference, %0ano doubt, to its milky juice. %0a%0a42 See the Clymenus, B. xxv. c. 33. %0a%0a%0a262 plint’s natural history. [Book XXVII. %0a%0amentioned, they facilitate delivery, and bring away the after¬ %0abirth. %0a%0aCHAP. 95. -PELECINON *. ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aWe have already® spoken of pelecinon as growing in corn¬ %0afields, a plant which throws out a number of shoots from %0athin stems, and has leaves like those of the chick-pea. The %0aseed, which is contained in pods of a curved shape, like %0adiminutive horns and three or four in number, is similar to %0agith 61 in appearance, bitter, and an excellent stomachic. It is %0aused as an ingredient in antidotes . 65 %0a%0aCHAP. 96. -POLYGALA : ONE REMEDY. %0a%0aPolygala 66 is a palm in height, with leaves like those of the %0alentil at the extremity of the stem. It has an astringent taste; %0ataken in drink, it increases the milk in nursing women. %0a%0aCHAP. 97. -POTERION, PHRYNION, OR NEURAS : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%0aPoterion , 67 or, as some call it, “ phrynion” or “ neuras,”® %0athrows out numerous branches, is shrivelled and prickly, and %0acovered with a thick down. The leaves of it are small and %0around; the branches long, soft, thin, and flexible; and the %0ablossom elongated, and of a grass-green colour. The seed is %0anever used, but it has a pungent flavour and a powerful smell: %0athe plant is found growing upon moist, watery, elevations. %0aThe roots are two or three in number, some two cubits in %0alength, sinewy, white, and firm. It is dug up in autumn, and %0athe stem yields a juice like gum, when cut. The root is said %0ato be of wonderful efficacy as an application for the cure of %0awounds, more particularly of the sinews, even when severed. %0aA decoction of it is also taken, with honey, for relaxations of %0athe sinews, and for weakness or wounds of those parts. %0a%0a63 In B. xviii. c. 44. It was also called “ securidaca.” %0a%0a64 See B. xx. c. 71. %0a%0a65 We learn from Galen that it formed an ingredient in the great anti¬ %0adote of Mithridates. %0a%0a66 Fee thinks that it may possibly be the Polygala vulgaris of Linnaeus, the %0aCommon milk-wort. Desfontaines mentions the Polygala amara of Lin¬ %0anaeus, the Bitter milkwort of the South of Europe; and Littre gives the %0aPolygala venulosa of Sibthorp. %0a%0a67 See B. xxv. c. 70. 66 The “ sinew ” plant. %0a%0a%0a203 %0a%0a%0aChap. 100.] THE PHTLLON. %0a%0aCHAP. 98. -THE PHALANGITIS, PHALANGION, Ofi LF.UCACANTHA : %0a%0aFOUR REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe phalangitis 69 is by some called “ phalangion,” and by %0aothers “ leucanthemum ,” 70 or, as I find it written in some %0acopies, “ leucacantha .” 71 Its branches are diminutive, never %0aless than two in number, and running in contrary directions : %0athe blossom is white, and similar to the flower of the red lily ; %0athe seed dark and broad, resembling the half of a lentil, but %0amuch thinner; and the root slender and of a grass-green colour. %0aThe leaves, blossoms, or seed of this plant are employed for %0athe cure of wounds inflicted by Bcorpions, serpents, and the %0aphalangium , 72 and for the removal of griping pains in the %0abowels. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 99. -THE PHYTEUMA : ONE PROPERTY'. %0a%0aAs for the phyteuma , 73 I think it a mere loss of time to %0adescribe it, it being only used as an ingredient in philtres. %0a%0aCHAP 100. -THE PHYLLON : ONE PROPERTY. %0a%0aThe Greeks give the name of “phyllon ” 74 td a plant which %0agrows among the rocks, in mountainous spots. The female %0aplant is of a more grass-green colour than the other, with a %0athin stem, a diminutive root, and a round seed, like that of the %0apoppy. This last kind ensures the conception of issue of the %0asame sex; Yvhile the male plant, differing only in the seed, %0awhich resembles the olive at its first appearance, ensures the %0aconception of male issue. They are both taken in wine. %0a%0a69 Generally identified with the Anthericum or Hemerocallis liliastrum %0aof Linnaeus, the Savoy anthericum or Spider’s-wort. M Fraassays. how¬ %0aever (Synopsis, p. 288), that that plant has not been found in Greece ; and %0arelying upon the description of Dioscorides, he prefers the Lloydia Graeca, %0awhich grows commonly in Attica, the isles of Greece, and the Peloponnesus, %0aas its synonym. It is found upon elevations of 1500 feet. %0a%0a70 *« \yhite flower.” 71 “ White thorn.” %0a%0a71 Hence its name. See B. viii. c. 41, B. x. c. 95, and B. xi. cc. 24, %0a28, 29. %0a%0a73 Most probably the Reseda phyteuma of Linnaeus, the Crosswort. %0a%0a71 See B. xxii. c. 18, and B. xxvi. c. 91. Fee thinks that it is two plants, %0athe Cnicus Casabonae, and the Thelygonum cynocrambe of Linnaeus, that %0aare here spoken of. Littre gives the Mercurialis perennis of Linnaeus, %0aBog's mercury, as its synonym. %0a%0a%0a264 %0a%0a%0aFlint’s natural history. %0a%0a%0a[Book XXVII. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 101. —THE FHELLANDKION : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe phellandrion 75 grows in marshy spots, and has a leaf like %0athat of parsley : the seed of it is taken in drink for calculi und %0aaffections of the bladder. %0a%0aCHAP. 102. -THE PHALARIS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe phalaris 76 has a long thin stem, like a reed, with a %0adrooping flower at the extremity; the seed is like that of %0asesame . 17 This plant, too, taken with milk and honey, in wine %0aor vinegar, breaks urinary calculi, und is curative of diseases %0aof the bladder. %0a%0aCHAP. 103. -THE POLYRRHIZON : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe polyrrhizon 79 has leaves like those of myrtle, and %0anumerous roots. These roots are pounded and administered %0ain wine, for injuries inflicted by serpents : they are useful, also, %0afor cattle. %0a%0aCHAP. 104. -THE PHOSERPINACA : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe proserpinaca , 79 a common plant enough, is an excellent %0aremedy for the sting of the scorpion. Powdered and mixed %0awith brine and oil, in which the maena 80 has been preserved, it %0ais an excellent cure, they say, for quinzy . 81 It is also stated %0athat, however fatigued a person may be, to the extent even of %0alosing his voice, he will be sure to be refreshed,., by putting this %0aplant beneath his tongue ; and that if it is eaten, a vomit will %0abe the result, productive of good effects. %0a%0a78 Linn®us has given to the Fine-leaved water-hemlock the name of %0aPhellandrium aquaticum, but the seeds of that plant are an active poison. %0aIt is probable that the Phellandrium, or “Male-cork-plant” of Pliny, %0astill remains unknown. %0a%0a76 Possibly the Phalaris aquatica of Linnaeus, the Water canary-grass. %0aLittre gives as its synonym, the Phalaris nodosa of Linnaeus, Knotted %0acanary-grass. See Beckmann, Hist. lnv. Vol. I. p. 34, Bohn’s Ed. %0a%0a77 This is an exaggeration; Dioscorides says “ millet.” %0a%0a78 Possibly the plant mentioned in B. xxv. c. 54; though the Aristo- %0alochia has not leaves like those of the myrtle. %0a%0a79 Supposed to be identical with the Polygonos, mentioned above in c. 91. %0a%0a80 See B. ix. c. 42, and B. xxvi. c. 11. From this passage it would %0a%0aappear that the maena was preserved in a somewhat similar way to our %0aSardines. 81 See B. xxvi. c. 11. %0a%0a%0aChap. 106.] %0a%0a%0aTHE RESEDA. %0a%0a%0a265 %0a%0a%0aciur. 105.— rhacoma: thirty-six remedies. %0a%0aRhacoma 82 is imported from the regions situate beyond %0aPontus. 8 * The root of it is similar to black costus, 81 but %0asmaller and somewhat redder, inodorous, and of a hot, astrin¬ %0agent flavour; when pounded, it yields a colour like that of %0awine, 6 * but inclining to saffron. Applied topically, it reduces %0aabscesses and inflammations, and heals wounds: used with %0araisin wine, it allays defluxions of the eyes; with honey, ecchy- %0amosis; and with vinegar, livid marks upon the skin. Reduced %0ato powder, it is sprinkled upon malignant ulcers, and is given %0ainternally for spitting of hlood, in doses of one drachma, in %0awater. For dysentery and coeliac affections, if unattended %0awith fever, it is administered in wine; but if there is fever, in %0awater. It is pounded more easily when it has been steeped in %0awater the night before. A decoction of it is given, in doses %0aof two drachmae, for ruptures, convulsions, contusions, and falls %0awith violence. %0a%0aIn cases of pains in the chest, a little pepper and myrrh is %0aadded. When the stomach is deranged, it is taken in cold %0awater; and the same in cases of chronic cough, purulent ex¬ %0apectorations, liver complaint, affections of the Bpleen, sciatica, %0adiseases of the kidneys, asthma, and hardness of breathing. %0aPounded and taken in doses of three oboli, in raisin wine, or %0aused in the form of a decoction, it cures irritations of the tra¬ %0achea : applied with vinegar, it acts as a detergent upon lichens. %0aIt is taken in drink, also, for flatulency, cold shiverings, chilly %0afevers, hiccup, gripiugs of the bowels, herpetic ulcerations, %0aoppressions of the head, vertigo attended with melancholy, %0alassitude accompanied with pain, and convulsions. %0a%0achap. 106.— the reseda: two remedies. %0a%0aIn the vicinity of Arimiuum, there is a well-known plant %0acalled “ reseda r” 86 it disperses abscesses and all kinds of in¬ %0aflammations. Those who employ it for these purposes, add %0a%0abJ The reading of this word is very doubtful. It is generally supposed %0ato be the Rheum Rhaponticum of Linnaeus, Pontic rhubarb. %0a%0aM The shores of the Euxine. %0a%0a81 See B. xii. c. 25. %0a%0aK “Fulvum,” probably, “tawny-coloured,” not white, red, or black; %0asee B. xiv. cc. 11, 18. %0a%0aw Possibly the Reseda alba of Linnaeus. %0a%0a%0a266 %0a%0a%0apliny’s natural history. [Book XXVii. %0a%0a%0athe following words : “ Reseda, 1 " 7 allay this disease ! knowest %0athou not, knowest thou not, what chick it is that has tom up %0athese roots ? Let it have nor head nor feet l” 88 This formula %0ais repeated thrice, the party spitting on the ground each time. %0a%0aCHAP. 107. -THESTCECHAS: THREE REMEDIES. %0a%0aThe stoechas 89 grows only in the islands of that name. 90 It %0ais an odoriferous plant, with leaves like those of hyssop, and %0aof a bitter taste. Taken in drink, it promotes menstruation, %0aand allays pains in the chest. It forms an ingredient, also, in %0a• antidotes. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 108. -THE SOLANUM, BY THE GREEKS CALLED STRYCHNON : %0a%0aTWO REMEDIAL PROPERTIES. %0a%0a%0a%25 %0a%0aThe solanum, 91 according to Cornelius Celsus, 93 is called %0a“strychnon ” by the Greeks; it is possessed of repercussive aud %0arefrigerative properties. %0a%0a%0aCHAP. 109. -SMYRNION : THIRTY-TWO REMEDIES. SINON : TWO %0a%0aREMEDIES. %0a%0aSmymion 93 has a stem like that of parsley, but larger leaves, %0aand growing principally about the youug shoots, which are %0anumerous. From the midst of these shoots the leaves make %0atheir appearance, unctuous, and bending towards the ground. %0aThis plant has a