diff:1673559211:1673559211:=1,3854d0%0a%3c BOOK XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c A DESCRIPTION OF PLANTS, AND OF THE REMEDIES DE¬ %0a%3c RIVED FROM THEM. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 1. (1.)—BESEABCHES OF THE ANCIENTS UPON THIS %0a%3c SUBJECT. %0a%3c %0a%3c The farther I proceed in this work, the more I am impressed %0a%3c with admiration of the ancients ; and the greater the number %0a%3c of plants that remain to be described, the more I am induced %0a%3c to venerate the zeal displayed by the men of former times in %0a%3c their researches, and the kindly spirit manifested by them in %0a%3c transmitting to us the results thereof. Indeed their bounteous¬ %0a%3c ness in this respect would almost seem to have surpassed the %0a%3c munificent disposition even of Nature herself, if our knowledge %0a%3c of plants had depended solely upon man’s spirit of discovery : %0a%3c but as it is, it is evident beyond all doubt that this knowledge %0a%3c has emanated from the gods themselves, or, at all events, has %0a%3c been the result of divine inspiration, even in those cases where %0a%3c man has been instrumental in communicating it to us. In %0a%3c other words, if we must confess the truth—a marvel surpassed %0a%3c by nothing in our daily experience—Nature herself, that %0a%3c common parent of all things, has at once produced them, and %0a%3c has discovered to us their properties. %0a%3c %0a%3c Wondrous indeed is it, that a Scythian 1 plant should he %0a%3c brought from the shores of the Palus Maeotis, and the euphor¬ %0a%3c bia 2 from Mount Atlas and the regions beyond the Pillars of %0a%3c Hercules, localities where the operations of Nature have reached %0a%3c their utmost limit ! That in another direction, the plant %0a%3c britannica 2 * should he conveyed to us from isles of the %0a%3c Ocean situate beyond the confines of the earth ! 3 That the %0a%3c ffithiopis 1 should reach us from a climate scorched by the %0a%3c %0a%3c 1 He alludes to the Glycyrrhiza or Scythice, our Liquorice, which is %0a%3c still found on the hanks of the river Volga. See B. xxi. c. 54, B. xxii. %0a%3c c. 11, B. xxv. c. 43, and B. xxvi. cc. 15, 87. %0a%3c %0a%3c 2 See B. xxv. c. 38. 2 * See B. xxv. c. 6. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 “ Extra terras.” Meaning, the continental part of the earth. %0a%3c %0a%3c * See o. 3 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 218 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINY’S NATUUAL HISTOBY. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c luminaries of heaven! And then, in addition to all this, that %0a%3c there should be a perpetual interchange going on between all %0a%3c parts of the earth, of productions so instrumental to the welfare %0a%3c of mankind ! Results, all of them, ensured to us by the peace %0a%3c that reigns under the majestic sway of the Roman power, a %0a%3c peace which brings in presence of each other, not individuals %0a%3c only, belonging to lands and nations far separate, hut moun¬ %0a%3c tains even, and heights towering above the clouds, their plants %0a%3c and their various productions ! That this great bounteousness %0a%3c of the gods may know no end, is my prayer, a bounteousness %0a%3c which seems to have granted the Roman sway as a second %0a%3c luminary for the benefit of mankind. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 2. (2.)—ACONITE, OTHEBW18E CALLED THELYPHONON, CAM- %0a%3c MABON, PABD ALI AN CUES, OB SCOBPIO ; FOUB BEMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c But who, I say, can sufficiently venerate the zeal and spirit of %0a%3c research displayed by the ancients ? It is they who have shown %0a%3c us that aconite is the most prompt of all poisons in its effects %0a%3c —so much so indeed, that female animals, if the sexual parts* %0a%3c are but touched with it, will not survive a single day. With %0a%3c this poison it was that M. Caecilius 6 accused Calpurnius Bestia %0a%3c of killing his wives in their sleep, and this it was that gave %0a%3c rise to that fearful peroration of his, denouncing the murderous %0a%3c finger of the accused. 7 According to the fables of mythology, %0a%3c this plant was originally produced from the foam of the dog %0a%3c Cerberus, when dragged by Hercules from the Infernal 8 Re¬ %0a%3c gions ; for which reason, it is said, it is still so remarkably %0a%3c abundant in the vicinity of Heraclea in Pontus, a spot where %0a%3c the entrance is still pointed out to the shades below. %0a%3c %0a%3c And yet, noxious as it is, the ancients have shown us how to %0a%3c employ aconite for the benefit of mankind, and have taught us %0a%3c as the result of their experience, that, taken in mulled wine, %0a%3c it neutralizes the venom of the scorpion : indeed such is the %0a%3c nature of this deadly plant, that it kills man, unless it can find %0a%3c %0a%3c 5 See B. xxv. c. 75. %0a%3c %0a%3c 6 Properly “ Caelius ”—the same M. Caelius Rufus who is mentioned %0a%3c in B. vii. c. 50. See also B. xxxv. c. 46. %0a%3c %0a%3c 7 “ Hinc ilia atrox peroratio ejus in digitum.” Sillig is probably right %0a%3c %0a%3c in his suggestion that the word “ mortiferum ” is wanting at the end of %0a%3c the sentence. Bestia was accused of having killed his wives by the %0a%3c contact of aconite, applied, through the agency of the finger, to the secret %0a%3c parts. 8 See B. vi. c. i. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 2.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ACONITE. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 219 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c in man something else to kill. When such is the case, as %0a%3c though it had discovered in the body a fit rival to contend with, %0a%3c that substance is the sole object of its attack ; finding another %0a%3c poison in the viscera, to it alone it confines its onslaught; %0a%3c and thus, a truly marvellous thing ! two poisons, each of them %0a%3c of a deadly nature, destroy one another within the body, and %0a%3c the man survives. Even more than this, the ancients have %0a%3c handed down to us remedies employed by the animals them¬ %0a%3c selves, and have shown how that venomous creatures even effect %0a%3c their own cure. By the contact of aconite the scorpion is %0a%3c struck with torpor, 9 is quite benumbed, assumes a pallid hue, %0a%3c and so confesses itself vanquished. When this is the case, %0a%3c white hellebore is its great auxiliary: the very touch of it dis- %0a%3c pels its torpor, and the aconite is forced to yield before two %0a%3c foes, its own enemy 10 and the common 11 enemy of all. %0a%3c %0a%3c Now, after this, if any one should be of opinion that man %0a%3c could, by any chance or possibility, make such discoveries as %0a%3c these, he must surely be guilty of ingratitude in thus appre¬ %0a%3c ciating the beneficence of the gods! In countries frequented %0a%3c by the panther, they rub meat with aconite, and if one of %0a%3c those animals should but taste it, its effects are fatal: indeed %0a%3c were not these means adopted, the country would soon be over¬ %0a%3c run by them. It is for this reason, too, that some persons %0a%3c have given to hellebore the name of “ pardalianches.” 12 It has %0a%3c been well ascertained, however, that the panther instantaneously %0a%3c recovers if it can find the opportunity of eating human ordure. 13 %0a%3c So far as these animals are concerned, who can entertain a %0a%3c doubt that it was chance only that first led them to this dis¬ %0a%3c covery ; and that as often as this happens the discovery is only %0a%3c a mere repetition of the accident, there being neither reason %0a%3c nor an appreciation of experience to ensure its transmission %0a%3c among them ? %0a%3c %0a%3c (3.) It is chance, 14 yes, it is chance that is the Deity who %0a%3c has made to us these numerous revelations for our practical %0a%3c %0a%3c * See B. xxv. c. 75. %0a%3c %0a%3c 10 The hellebore. See B. xxiii. c. 75, and B. xxv. c. 21. %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 The scorpion. 12 “ Pard-strangle.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 13 See B. viii. c. 41. %0a%3c %0a%3c 14 He seems here, by implication, to contradict himself, and, by bis ex¬ %0a%3c planation, to be sensible that be does so. He would appear not to have %0a%3c known exactly wbat bis belief was in reference to first causes. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 220 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pltni’s natural history. [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c benefit ; 15 always understanding that under this name we mean %0a%3c Nature, that great parent and mistress of all things : and this %0a%3c is evident, whether we come to the conclusion, that these wild %0a%3c beasts make the discovery from day to day, or that they are %0a%3c gifted from the first with these powers of perception. Re. %0a%3c garded in another point of view, it really is a disgrace that %0a%3c all animated beings should have an exact knowledge of what %0a%3c is beneficial to them, with the exception of man ! %0a%3c %0a%3c The ancients, openly professing their belief that there is no %0a%3c evil without some admixture of good, have asserted that aconite %0a%3c is a remarkably useful ingredient in compositions for the eyes. %0a%3c It may therefore be permitted me, though I have hitherto %0a%3c omitted a description of the poisonous plants, to point out the %0a%3c characteristics of aconite, if only that it may be the more %0a%3c easily detected. Aconite 16 has leaves like those of cyclaminos 1 ’ %0a%3c or of the cucumber, never more than four in number, slightly %0a%3c hairy, and rising from near the root. This root, which is of %0a%3c moderate size, resembles the sea-fish known as the “cam- %0a%3c marus,” 18 a circumstance owing to which the plant has received %0a%3c the name of “ cammaron ” from some; while others, for the %0a%3c reason already 19 mentioned, have called it “ thelyphonon.’’ M %0a%3c The root is slightly curved, like a scorpion’s tail, for which %0a%3c reason some persons have given it the name of “scorpio.” %0a%3c Others, again, have preferred giving it the name of “ myoc- %0a%3c tonon,” 21 from the fact that the odour of it kills mice at a %0a%3c considerable distance even. %0a%3c %0a%3c This plant is found growing upon the naked rocks known %0a%3c as “ aconae ;” 22 and hence it is, according to some authorities, %0a%3c %0a%3c 15 “ Hoc habet nomen ” is omitted ; for, as Sillig says, it is evidently a %0a%3c gloss, which has crept into the text. %0a%3c %0a%3c 16 The ancients no doubt knew several plants under the common name %0a%3c of Aconitum. The one here described, is identified by Fee with the Do- %0a%3c ronicum pardalianches of Linnaeus, Leopard’s bane. %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 See B. xxv. c. 67. Fee says that neither the leaves of the Doronicum, %0a%3c nor of any plant of the genus Arnica, bear any resemblance to those of %0a%3c the Cyclamen, or the cucumber. He remarks also, that the contact solely %0a%3c of it is not productive of poisonous effects. %0a%3c %0a%3c 18 A kind of crab. 19 At the beginning of this Chapter. %0a%3c %0a%3c 20 “ Female-bane,” or “ female-killer.” See B. xx. c. 23. %0a%3c %0a%3c 21 “ Mice-killer.” This assertion is incorrect. %0a%3c %0a%3c 22 So called from a, “without,” and koviq, “dust.” Theophrastus %0a%3c says that it received its name from the town of Aeon®, in the vicinity of %0a%3c which it grew in great abundance. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 4.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c AGERATON. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 221 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c that it is called “ aconitum,” there being not so much as dust %0a%3c even about it to conduce to its nutriment. Such is the reason %0a%3c given for its name by some : but according to others, it re¬ %0a%3c ceives this appellation from the fact that it fatally exercises the %0a%3c same effects upon the body that the whetstone 23 does upon the %0a%3c edge of iron, being no sooner employed than its effects are felt. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 3. (4.)- A5TH10PIS I FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c .Ethiopis 24 is a plant with leaves resembling those of phlo- %0a%3c mos,“ large, numerous, hairy, and springing from the root. %0a%3c The stem is square, rough, similar to that of arction 35 * in ap¬ %0a%3c pearance, and with numerous axillary concavities. The seed %0a%3c resembles that of the fitch, being white and twofold ; the roots %0a%3c are several in number, long, fleshy, soft, and of a viscous taste ; %0a%3c when dry they turn black and hard, and might easily be taken %0a%3c for horns. In addition to ^Ethiopia, this plant grows upon %0a%3c Mount Ida in Troas, and in Messenia. The roots are gathered %0a%3c in autumn, and left to dry for some days in the sun, to prevent %0a%3c them from turning mouldy. Taken in white wine they are %0a%3c curative of affections of the uterus, and a decoction of them %0a%3c is administered for sciatica, pleurisy, and eruptions of the %0a%3c throat. The kind, however, which comes from ^Ethiopia, is %0a%3c by far the best, and gives instantaneous relief. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 4. -AGERATON : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Ageraton 26 is a ferulaceous plant, a couple of palms in height, %0a%3c similar to origanum 27 in appearance, and bearing flowers like %0a%3c balls of gold. Used as a fumigation, this plant acts as a %0a%3c diuretic; and as a detergent upon the uterus, when used in a %0a%3c . sitting bath more particularly. Its name has been given to it, %0a%3c from the circumstance that it keeps a very long time without %0a%3c fading. %0a%3c %0a%3c 25 Also called cikovt]. %0a%3c %0a%3c 21 Generally identified with the Salvia argentea of Linnaeus, Silver sage, %0a%3c or else with the Salvia JEthiopis, Woolly sage. It must not be confounded %0a%3c with the plant of the same name mentioned in B. xxiv. c. 102. %0a%3c %0a%3c 24 See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a%3c %0a%3c :i * See c. 16 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 26 “Not growing old.’’ It is identified by Fee and Desfontaines with %0a%3c %0a%3c the Acbillaea ageratum of Linnaeus, Sweet milfoil or Maudlin. Littre %0a%3c gives as its synonym, the Hypericum origanifolium. • %0a%3c %0a%3c 27 See B. xx. c. 67. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 222 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint's nattjb.il histoby. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 5.—THE ALOE ; TWENTY-NINE KEMEDIE8. %0a%3c %0a%3c The aloe 28 bears a resemblance to the squill, except that it is %0a%3c larger, and has more substantial leaves, with streaks running %0a%3c obliquely. The stem is tender, red in the middle, and not %0a%3c unlike that of the anthericus. 29 It has a single root, which runs %0a%3c straight downwards, like a stake driven into the ground; its %0a%3c smell is powerful, and it has a bitter taste. The most esteemed %0a%3c aloes are those imported from India, but it grows in the Asiatic %0a%3c provinces 30 as well. This last kind, however, is never used, %0a%3c except that the leaves are applied fresh to wounds; indeed, %0a%3c these leaves, as well as the juice, are glutinous to a marvellous %0a%3c degree, and it is for this property that it is grown in vessels of %0a%3c a conical form, in the same way as the greater aizoiim. 31 Some %0a%3c persons make incisions in the stem to obtain the j uice, before %0a%3c the 6eed is ripe, while others, again, make them in the leaves %0a%3c as well. Tearlike drops are also found adhering to it, which %0a%3c exude spontaneously: hence it is that some recommend that %0a%3c the place should be paved where it is grown, to prevent this %0a%3c juice from being absorbed. %0a%3c %0a%3c Some authors have stated, that there is found in Judaea, %0a%3c beyond Hierosolyma, a mineral 32 aloe, but that it is inferior to %0a%3c the other kinds, being of a darker colour and more humid than %0a%3c any of the rest. Aloes 53 of the finest quality should be %0a%3c unctuous and shining, of a red colour, brittle, compact, like %0a%3c the substance of liver, and easily liquefied. That which is %0a%3c hard and black should be rejected; the same, too, when it is %0a%3c mixed with sand or adulterated with gum and acacia, a fraud %0a%3c which may be easily detected by the taste. %0a%3c %0a%3c This plant is of an astringent nature, binding, and slightly %0a%3c calorific. It is employed for numerous purposes, but principally %0a%3c as a purgative, 34 it being almost the only one of all the medica- %0a%3c %0a%3c 28 The ancients probably included under this name several distinct species %0a%3c of the aloe. They were well acquainted, Fee says, with the Indian aloe, %0a%3c but probably not with that of Africa. As described by Pliny, he identifies %0a%3c it with the Aloe perfoliata of Linnaeus: Desfontaines gives the Aloe %0a%3c umbellata. 29 See B. xxi. c. 68. 30 “ Asia." %0a%3c %0a%3c 31 See B. xxv. c. 102. The aloe is still grown in large wooden vessels, %0a%3c in this country, at least; but only as an ornament. %0a%3c %0a%3c 32 He alludes to the bitumen of Judaea, much used by the Egyptians for %0a%3c the purposes of embalmment. %0a%3c %0a%3c 33 He is speaking of the prepared aloes of commerce. %0a%3c %0a%3c 31 It is still used for this purpose. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 5.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE ALOE. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 223 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c raents which produce that effect, that is at the same time a %0a%3c good stomachic, and does not exercise the slightest noxious %0a%3c influence upon the stomach. It is taken in doses of one %0a%3c drachma, and, in cases of derangement of the stomach, it is %0a%3c administered two or three times a day, in the proportion of %0a%3c one spoonful to two cyathi of warm or cold water, at intervals, %0a%3c according to the nature of the emergency. As a purgative it %0a%3c is mostly taken in doses of three drachmae; and it operates %0a%3c still more efficaciously, if food is eaten directly afterwards. %0a%3c Used with astringent wine, it prevents 35 the hair from falling %0a%3c off, the head being rubbed with it the contrary way of the %0a%3c hair, in the sun. Applied to the temples and forehead with %0a%3c rose oil and vinegar, or used as an infusion, in a more diluted %0a%3c form, it allays head-ache. It is generally agreed that it is %0a%3c remedial for all diseases 36 of the eyes, but more particularly for %0a%3c prurigo and scaly eruptions of the eye-lids ; as also for marks %0a%3c and bruises, applied in combination with honey, Pontic honey %0a%3c in particular. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is employed,also, for affections of the tonsillary glands and %0a%3c gums, for all ulcerations of the mouth, and for spitting of %0a%3c blood, if not in excess—the proper dose being one drachma, %0a%3c taken in water or else vinegar. Used by itself, or in combination %0a%3c with vinegar, it arrests haemorrhage, whether proceeding from %0a%3c wounds or from other causes. In addition to these properties, it %0a%3c is extremely efficacious for the cure of wounds, producing %0a%3c cicatrization very rapidly : it is sprinkled also upon ulcerations %0a%3c of the male organs, and is applied to condylomata and chaps %0a%3c oi the fundament, either in common wine, raisin wine, or by %0a%3c itself in a dry state, according as a mollifying or restrictive %0a%3c treatment is required. It has the effect, also, of gently %0a%3c arresting haemorrhoidal bleeding, when in excess. In cases of %0a%3c dysentery, it is used as an injection, and where the digestion %0a%3c is imperfect it is taken shortly after the evening meal. For %0a%3c jaundice, it is administered in doses of three oboli, in %0a%3c water. As a purgative for the bowels, it is taken in pills, with %0a%3c boiled honey or turpentine. It is good also for the removal of %0a%3c hangnails. When employed in ophthalmic preparations, it is %0a%3c first washed, that the more gravelly portions of it may subside; %0a%3c %0a%3c M There is no foundation, Fee says, for this statement. %0a%3c %0a%3c M It would appear that it is still employed in India for this purpose, %0a%3c but it is no longer used in Europe. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 224 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c plint’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c or else it is put over the fire in a pipkin, and stirred with a %0a%3c feather from time to time, that the w hole of it may be equally %0a%3c warmed. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAT. 6.—ALCEA : ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c Alcea 37 is a plant with leaves, resembling those of vervain," %0a%3c known also as “ peristereon,” some three or four stems %0a%3c covered with leaves, a flower like that of the rose, and white %0a%3c roots, at most six in number, a cubit in length, and running %0a%3c obliquely. It grows in a soil that is rich without being dry. %0a%3c The root is given in wine or water, for dysentery, diarrhoea, %0a%3c ruptures, and convulsions. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 7.-THE ALYPON : ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c The alypon 39 has a small stem, with a soft head, and is not %0a%3c unlike beet in appearance. It has an acrid, viscous taste, %0a%3c extremely pungent and burning. Taken in hydromel, with %0a%3c a little sailt, it acts as a purgative. The smallest dose is two %0a%3c drachmae, a moderate dose, four, and the largest, six. When %0a%3c used as a purgative, it is taken in chicken broth. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 8. -ALSINE, A PLANT USED FOR THE SAME PURPOSES AS %0a%3c %0a%3c HELXINE : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Alsine, 40 a plant known as “myosoton” 41 to some, grows in the %0a%3c woods, to which fact it is indebted for its name of “ alsine.” 42 %0a%3c It begins to make its appearance at mid-winter, and withers in %0a%3c the middle of summer. When it first puts forth, the leaves %0a%3c bear a strong resemblance to the ears of mice. We shall have %0a%3c %0a%3c 37 Identified by Fee with the Malva alcea of Linnaeus, the Vervain %0a%3c mallow, an emollient and, comparatively, inert plant. Littre gives as %0a%3c its synonym the Malope malacho'ides, Marsh mallow. Sibthorp identifies %0a%3c it with the Hibiscus trionum, and Anguillara with the Althaea canryibina %0a%3c of Linnaeus. It is probably the same plant as the Alcima, mentioned several %0a%3c times in B. xxvi. 38 See B. xxv. c. 59. %0a%3c %0a%3c 39 Identified with the Globularia alypum of Linnaeus, the Three-toothed %0a%3c leaf Globularia, or Turbith. %0a%3c %0a%3c 40 Identified by Sprengel with the Cerastium aquaticum, and by other %0a%3c %0a%3c authorities with the Alsine media of Linnaeus, the Common chickweed. %0a%3c Desfontaines suggests the Stellaria nemorum, the Broadleaved stitchwort, %0a%3c but Fee prefers the Parietaria Cretica of Linnaeus, Cretan pellitory, as its %0a%3c synonym. 41 “ Mouse-ear.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 42 From the Greek akooc, a “ grove.” %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 10.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ANDEOSAMON. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 225 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c occasion, 43 however, to speak of another plant, which may, %0a%3c with much more justice, be called “ myosotis.” As for alsine, it %0a%3c would be the same thing as helxine, 44 were it not that it is smaller %0a%3c and not so hairy. It grows in 45 gardens, and upon walls more %0a%3c particularly : when rubbed, it emits a smell like that of cucum¬ %0a%3c ber. It is used for abscesses, inflammations, and all those pur¬ %0a%3c poses for which helxine is employed ; its properties, however, %0a%3c are not so active. It is applied topically, also, to defluxions of %0a%3c the eyes, and to sores upon the generative organs, and ulcera¬ %0a%3c tions, with barley meal. The juice is used as an injection for %0a%3c the ears. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 9.-THE ANDKOSACES : SIX REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The androsaces 46 is a white plant, bitter, without leaves, and %0a%3c bearing arms surmounted with follicules, containing the seed. %0a%3c It grows in the maritime parts of Syria, more particularly. %0a%3c This plant is administered for dropsy, in doses of two drachmae, %0a%3c pounded or boiled, in either -water, wine, or vinegar: it acts %0a%3c most powerfully as a diuretic. It is used also for gout, either %0a%3c taken internally or used as a liniment. The seed is possessed %0a%3c of similar properties. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 10.—ANDROSJEMON OE ASCYEON : SIX REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Androssemon 47 or, as some persons call it, “ascyron,” is not %0a%3c unlike hypericon, a plant of which we have spoken already : 48 %0a%3c the stems, however, are larger, redder, and lie more closely %0a%3c together. The leaves are of a white colour, and like those of %0a%3c rue in shape; the seed resembles that of the black poppy, and %0a%3c the upper branches, when bruised, emit a red juice the colour %0a%3c of blood: these branches have also a resinous smell. %0a%3c %0a%3c This plant grows in vineyards, and it is usually in the middle %0a%3c %0a%3c 43 In c. 80 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 44 The Parietaria officinalis; see B. xxii. c. 19. %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 He has previously stated that it grows in the woods. The fact is, %0a%3c M. Fraas says, that it grows equally upon garden walls, heaps of rubbish, %0a%3c in plains, upon shady rocks, and upon mountains, below an elevation of %0a%3c 1500 feet. %0a%3c %0a%3c 46 Generally supposed not to be a vegetable production, but a Madrepore. %0a%3c Fee identifies it with the Madrepora acetabulum of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 47 “ Man’s blood.” Identified by Sprengel with the Hypericum monta- %0a%3c num, and by Sibtliorp and Fee with the Hypericum perforatum, of Lin¬ %0a%3c naeus, Perforated tutsan or St. John’s wort. 48 See B. xxvi. cc. 53, 54. %0a%3c %0a%3c VOL. V. Q %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 226 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c of autumn that it is taken up and hung to dry. Used as a %0a%3c purgative, it is bruised with the seed, and taken in the morn¬ %0a%3c ing or just after the evening meal, in doses of two drachmae, %0a%3c in hydromel, wine, or pure water, the draught amounting to %0a%3c one sextarius in all. It carries off bile, and is particularly %0a%3c good for sciatica; but in this last case, caper root must be %0a%3c taken with resin the day after, the dose being one drachma, %0a%3c to be repeated every four days : after being purged, it is the %0a%3c practice for the patient, if in robust health, to take wine, but %0a%3c if in a weak state of body, water. It is employed topically, %0a%3c also, for gout, burns, and wounds, as it tends to arrest the flow %0a%3c of blood. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 11.-AMBROSIA, BOTRYS, OR ARTEMISIA - . THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Ambrosia is a vague name, which has fluctuated between %0a%3c various plants : there is one, 49 however, which has been more %0a%3c particularly designated by this appellation, a branchy, shrub¬ %0a%3c like plant, with a thin stem, some three palms in height; the %0a%3c root of it is one third shorter, and the leaves, towards the lower %0a%3c part of the stem, resemble those of rue. Its diminutive %0a%3c branches bear a seed which hangs down in clusters, and has a %0a%3c vinous smell: hence it is that by some persons the plant is %0a%3c called “ botrys,” 80 while to others it is known as “ artemisia.” %0a%3c The people of Cappadocia use it for garlands. It is employed %0a%3c in medicine as a resolvent. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 12.-THE ANONIS OR 0N0NI8 : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The anonis, 81 by some called “ ononis” in preference, is a %0a%3c branchy plant, and similar to fenugreek in appearance, except %0a%3c that it is more shrub-like and more hairy. It has an agreeable %0a%3c smell, and becomes prickly after spring. It is pickled in brine %0a%3c for eating. Applied fresh to ulcers, it cauterizes the margins of %0a%3c them. Tor the cure of tooth-ache, the root is boiled in oxy- %0a%3c crate: taken in drink, with honey, the root expels urinary calculi. %0a%3c For epilepsy, it is administered in oxyrnel, boiled down to one %0a%3c half. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 13.-THE ANAGYROS OB ACOPON : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The anagyros, known to some by the name of “ aco- %0a%3c %0a%3c 49 Identified with the Ambrosia maritima of Linnaeus, the Sea ambrosia. %0a%3c %0a%3c 50 The “cluster” plant. It still figures in the Materia Medica. See %0a%3c %0a%3c B. xxv. c. 36, and c. 31 of this Book. ai g ee y X1 j 0t 58 . %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 15.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c APARINE. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 227 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pon,” 62 is a shrub-like plant, with an offensive smell, and a %0a%3c blossom like that of the cabbage. The seed grows in small %0a%3c hornlike pods of considerable length, and resembles a kidney %0a%3c in shape; it hardens about the time of harvest. The leaves of %0a%3c this plant are applied to gatherings, and are attached to the %0a%3c person in cases of difficult parturition, care being taken to %0a%3c remove them the moment after delivery. In cases where the %0a%3c extraction of the dead foetus is attended with difficulty, or where %0a%3c the after-birth or catamenia are retarded, the leaves are taken, in %0a%3c doses of one drachma, in raisin wine. The leaves are adminis¬ %0a%3c tered in the same manner for asthma: they are prescribed also %0a%3c in old wine, for injuries inflicted by the phalangium. 53 The %0a%3c root is employed medicinally as a resolvent and maturative: %0a%3c the seed, chewed, acts as an emetic. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAr. 14.-THE ANONYMOS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The anonymos, 54 through not having a name, has at last %0a%3c found one. 55 It is brought from Scythia, and has been highly %0a%3c extolled by Hicesius, a physician of no small repute, as also %0a%3c by Aristogiton. Bruised in water and applied, it is remarkably %0a%3c useful for wounds, and taken in drink it is good for blows upon %0a%3c the chest or mamillae, as also for spitting of blood: it has %0a%3c been thought, too, that it might be advantageously taken in a %0a%3c potion for wounds. I am of opinion that the additional state¬ %0a%3c ment, to the effect that, burnt fresh, it acts as a solder to iron %0a%3c or copper, is wholly fabulous. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 15. (5.)—APARINE, OMPHALOCABPOS, OB PHILANTHROPOS : %0a%3c %0a%3c THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Aparine, 56 otherwise called “ omphalocarpos” 57 or “ philan- %0a%3c thropos,” 53 is a ramose, hairy, plant, with five or six leaves at %0a%3c regular intervals, arranged circularly around the branches. %0a%3c %0a%3c 52 “ Dispelling lassitude.” Identified with the Anagyris fcetida of Lin- %0a%3c nffius, the Stinking bean trefoil. It is a purgative, and its seeds are emetic. %0a%3c %0a%3c 52 See B. viii. c. 41, B. x. c. 95, B. xi. cc. 24, 28. %0a%3c %0a%3c 54 It has not been identified, Pliny being the only author that has men¬ %0a%3c tioned it. The Ajuga pyramidalis of Linnaeus, and the Ajuga iva have %0a%3c been suggested. 55 “ Anonymos,” or “ nameless.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 56 See B. xviii. c. 44, and B. xxiv. c. 116. It is identified with the Galium %0a%3c Aparine of Linnaeus, Ladies’ bedstraw, Cleavers, goosegrass, hariff, or %0a%3c catchweed. Its medicinal properties are next to nothing. %0a%3c %0a%3c 51 “Navel-fruit.” w “Man-loving.” See B. xxiv. c. 116. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 228 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c The seed is round, hard, concave, and of a sweetish taste. It %0a%3c grows in cornfields, gardens, and meadows, and, by the aid of %0a%3c its prickly points, adheres to the clothes. The seed is em¬ %0a%3c ployed to neutralize the venom of serpents, being taken in %0a%3c doses of one drachma, in •wine : it is useful also for the bite of %0a%3c the phalangium. 59 The leaves, applied topically, arrest hae¬ %0a%3c morrhage from wounds. The juice is used as an injection for %0a%3c the ears. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 16.-THE ARCTION OK AKCT01UTM : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The arction C0 is by some called “ arcturum” in preference: %0a%3c the leaves of it are like those of verbascum, 61 except that they %0a%3c are more hairy; the stem is long and soft, and the seed resem¬ %0a%3c bles that of cummin. It grows in rocky localities, and has a %0a%3c tender root, white and sweet. A decoction of it is made with %0a%3c wine for tooth-ache, being retained for that purpose in the %0a%3c mouth. The plant is taken in drink for sciatica and strangury, %0a%3c and is applied with wine to burns and chilblains, which are %0a%3c fomented also with the root and seed bruised in wine. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 17.—THE ASPLENON OK HEMIONION : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Some persons call the asplenon 62 by the name of “ hemio- %0a%3c nion.” 63 It has numerous leaves, a third of a foot in length, %0a%3c and a slimy root, pierced with holes like that of fern, white, %0a%3c and hairy. It is destitute of stem, flower, and seed, 64 and is %0a%3c found growing upon rocks or sheltered damp walls. The most %0a%3c approved kind is that of Crete. A decoction of the leaves %0a%3c in vinegar, taken in drink for a period of thirty days, will %0a%3c %0a%3c 59 See Note 53 above. %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 Brotero and Linnaeus identify it with the Arctium lappa of Linnaeus, %0a%3c the Burdock or clot-burr: Sibthorp with the Conyza Candida, the White %0a%3c fleabane: others, again, with the Celsia arcturus of Linnaeus, and Sprengel %0a%3c with the Verbascum ferrugineum of Linnaeus, the Ferruginous mullein; %0a%3c between which two last, Fee is unable to decide. %0a%3c %0a%3c 61 See B. xxv. c. 73. %0a%3c %0a%3c 62 So called from its supposed property of consuming the spleen. It is %0a%3c generally identified with the Asplenium ceterach of Linnaeus, Spleenwort, %0a%3c or miltwaste. The Asplenium hemionitis of Linnaeus, Mule’s fern, and %0a%3c the Asplenium scolopendrium of Linnaeus, Hart’s tongue, have also been %0a%3c suggested; but Fee prefers the first-named plant. %0a%3c %0a%3c 63 The “ mule’s plant.” These animals rvere said to be very fond of it. %0a%3c %0a%3c 64 This is incorrect: the Ceterach has a large quantity of seed, but it %0a%3c is concealed beneath a kind of downy substance. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 20.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ASCYBON. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 229 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c consume the spleen, it is said, the leaves being applied simul¬ %0a%3c taneously. The leaves give relief also in hiccup. This plant %0a%3c should never be given to females, being productive of sterility. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 18.-THE ASCLEPIAS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The asclepias 65 has leaves like