r, and pro¬ %0a%3c vocative of saliva: the root of it is long and red. It grows %0a%3c upon rocks, to which circumstance it is indebted for its addi- %0a%3c tonal name of “ petraeonand is extremely useful 79 for affec¬ %0a%3c tions of the sides and kidneys, griping pains in the bowels, %0a%3c diseases of the chest and lungs, spitting of blood, and eruptions %0a%3c of the fauces. The root is pounded and taken in drink, or else %0a%3c a decoction is made of it in wine ; sometimes, also, it is ap¬ %0a%3c plied externally. Chewed, it allays thirst, and is particularly %0a%3c refreshing to the pulmonary organs. It is employed topically %0a%3c for sprains and contusions, and has a soothing effect upon the %0a%3c intestines. %0a%3c %0a%3c Cooked upon hot ashes, with the follicules removed, and %0a%3c then beaten up with nine peppercorns and taken in water, it %0a%3c acts astringently upon the bowels. Tor the cure of wounds it %0a%3c %0a%3c ,6 Identified by Desfontaines with the Symphytum officinale, or Great %0a%3c comfrey. Fee, however, considers it to be the Coris Monspeliensis of Lin¬ %0a%3c naeus, Montpellier coris. Lobel identifies it with the Prunella vulgaris of %0a%3c Linnaeus, Common self-heal, and Cajsalpinus with the Hyssopus officinalis %0a%3c of Linnaeus. See B. xxvi. c. 26. %0a%3c %0a%3c n Fee reiterates his assertion here that this “rock" symphytum is a %0a%3c totally different plant from the Symphytum officinale, or Comfrey, though %0a%3c they appear to have been generally considered as identical by Scribonius %0a%3c Largus, Plinius Valerianus, Apuleius, and other writers. %0a%3c %0a%3c 7,5 See B. xxvi. c. 26. %0a%3c %0a%3c 9 This account of its medicinal properties applies properly to the Sym¬ %0a%3c phytum officinale, or Great comfrey, a plant which would appear to have %0a%3c been confounded by Pliny with the Alum, if Fee is right in his conjecture. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 232 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINY’S NATURAL HI8T0EY. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book xxvir. %