till figures in the French Materia Medica, and that %0a%3c the lower classes use it in most of the cases mentioned by Pliny; he states %0a%3c also, that it is destitute of energetic properties, in a medicinal point of view. %0a%3c %0a%3c 81 2vn%3cpvrov, “ consolidating.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 82 See B. xiii. c. 48, and B. xxvi. c. 66. %0a%3c %0a%3c 83 The Actaea spicata of Linnaeus, Herb-christopher or bane-berries, is %0a%3c mentioned by Desfontaines; but Fee is inclined to identify it with the %0a%3c Sambucus ebulus of Linnaeus, the Dwarf elder, wall-wort, or dane-wort. %0a%3c %0a%3c 81 See B. xxiii. c, 14. 85 In B. xxi. cc. 33, 38. %0a%3c %0a%3c 86 The Artemisia Santonica of Linnaeus, Tartarian southernwood. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 28.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ABSINTHIUM. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 233 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c instance, so called from a city in Gaul, and the Pontic, 87 which %0a%3c comes from Pontus, where the cattle are fattened upon it—a %0a%3c diet which causes them to be destitute of gall. 88 The Pontic %0a%3c wormwood, we may remark, is of the finest quality, superior to %0a%3c that of Italy, 89 and much more bitter; the pith, however, of the %0a%3c Pontic wormwood is sweet. As to its general utility, a plant %0a%3c so commonly found and applied to such numerous uses, people %0a%3c are universally agreed ; but with the Romans more particularly %0a%3c it has been always held in the highest esteem, from the fact of %0a%3c its being employed in their religious ceremonials. Thus, for %0a%3c instance, upon the Latin 90 Festival, it is the custom to have a %0a%3c race of four-horsed chariots in the Capital, and for the conqueror %0a%3c to be presented with a draught of wormwood; from the circum¬ %0a%3c stance, no doubt, that our forefathers were of opinion that good %0a%3c health was the most valuable reward they could bestow upon %0a%3c his skill. %0a%3c %0a%3c This plant is very strengthening to the stomach, and hence %0a%3c it is that wines are flavoured with it, as already 91 stated. A %0a%3c decoction of it in water is also taken, the following being %0a%3c the method employed in preparing it. Six drachmae of the %0a%3c leaves are boiled, with the branches, in three sextarii of rain %0a%3c water, and the preparation is then left to cool in the open air a %0a%3c day and anight. Salt, too, should be added to it. When old, it %0a%3c is utterly useless. A dilution of wormwood steeped in water %0a%3c is also used, such being the name 92 given to this method of %0a%3c preparing it. This dilution is made by leaving the vessel %0a%3c covered up for three days, any kind of water being used. %0a%3c Pounded wormwood is but rarely employed, and the same %0a%3c with the extracted juice of the seed. 93 In cases, however, %0a%3c where it is extracted, the seed is subjected to pressure as soon %0a%3c as it begins to swell, after which it is soaked for three days %0a%3c in water, if used fresh, and seven, if dry. It is then boiled %0a%3c in a copper vessel, in the proportion of ten heminae to forty- %0a%3c five sextarii of water, after which it is strained off and boiled %0a%3c %0a%3c 87 The Artemisia Pontica of Linnaeus, Little wormwood, or Roman %0a%3c wormwood. 88 See B. xi. c. 75. %0a%3c %0a%3c 89 The Artemisia absinthium of Linnaeus, Common wormwood. %0a%3c %0a%3c 90 Upon which occasion a sacrifice was offered on the Alban Mount. %0a%3c See further as to this Festival, in B. iii. c. 2. %0a%3c %0a%3c 91 In B. xiv. c. 19. "Wine of wormwood is still used medicinally. %0a%3c %0a%3c 93 “Dilutum.” An infusion. %0a%3c %0a%3c 93 It contains a small quantity of essential oil. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 234 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint’s natural historv. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c gently to the consistency of honey, in the same way as the juice %0a%3c is extracted from the smaller centaury. The juice, however, %0a%3c of wormwood, thus extracted, is bad for the head and stomach; %0a%3c whereas the decoction, on the other hand, is wholesome in the %0a%3c highest degree, as it acts astringently upon the stomach, carries %0a%3c off bile, is a powerful diuretic, has a soothing effect upon the %0a%3c bowels, and assuages pains in the intestines. With the addi¬ %0a%3c tion of sile, 94 Gallic nard, and a little vinegar, it dispels nausea %0a%3c and flatulency, and expels intestinal worms. It removes %0a%3c qualmishness, promotes the digestion, and, with the addition %0a%3c of rue, pepper, and salt, disperses crudities of the stomach. %0a%3c %0a%3c The ancients were in the habit of giving wormwood as a %0a%3c purgative, the dose being six drachmae of the seed with three %0a%3c of salt and one cyathus of honey, in one sextarius of sea water %0a%3c kept for some time. This preparation, however, is rendered %0a%3c more efficacious by doubling the proportion of salt; the seed, %0a%3c too, must be bruised with the greatest care, as there is con¬ %0a%3c siderable difficulty in pounding it. Some authorities have %0a%3c prescribed the dose above mentioned to be given in polenta, 94 %0a%3c with the addition of pennyroyal; while others recommend %0a%3c the leaves to be given to children in a dried fig, to disguise %0a%3c their bitterness. Taken with iris, 96 wormwood acts as a %0a%3c detergent upon the thoracic organs: for jaundice it is used %0a%3c raw, with parsley or adiantum. 97 In cases of flatulency, it is %0a%3c sipped every now and then, warmed in water; for liver com¬ %0a%3c plaints it is taken with Gallic nard, and for diseases of the %0a%3c spleen, with vinegar, pap, 98 or figs. Taken in vinegar it neu¬ %0a%3c tralizes the bad effects of fungi and of viscus in wine it is %0a%3c an antidote to the poison of hemlock, and to the bite of the %0a%3c shrew-mouse, and is curative of wounds inflicted by the sea- %0a%3c dragon 1 and the scorpion. It contributes also very greatly to %0a%3c the improvement of the sight, and is used as an external appli¬ %0a%3c cation, with raisin wine, for defluxions of the eyes, and with %0a%3c honey, for bruises. %0a%3c %0a%3c 94 See B. xx. c. 18. 95 See B. xviii. c. 14. %0a%3c %0a%3c 96 See B. xxi. c. 19. 97 See B. xxii. c. 30. %0a%3c %0a%3c 93 “ Puls.” See B. xviii. c. 19. %0a%3c %0a%3c 99 From a passage in Scribonius Largus, c. 191, it has been concluded %0a%3c that by the word “ visco,” he means the juice of the Ixias or Chamaeleon, %0a%3c mentioned in B. xxii. c. 21. %0a%3c %0a%3c 1 See B. ix. c. 43, and B. xxxii. c. 53. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 29.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ABSINTHIUM MAEINUM. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 235 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c The steam of a decoction of wormwood is curative of affec¬ %0a%3c tions of the ears; and when they are attacked with running %0a%3c sores, a liniment of wormwood bruised with honey is applied. %0a%3c Three or four sprigs of wormwood, with one root of Gallic %0a%3c nard, taken in six cyathi of water, act as a diuretic and as %0a%3c an eramenagogue; indeed, if taken with honey, or employed %0a%3c as a pessary with wool, it has especial virtues as an emmena- %0a%3c gogue. In combination with honey and nitre it is useful for %0a%3c quinzy, and an infusion of it in water is good for epinyctis. %0a%3c A topical application is made of it for recent wounds, provided %0a%3c always they have not been touched with water: it is em¬ %0a%3c ployed also for ulcers upon the head. In combination with %0a%3c Cyprian wax or figs, it is highly recommended as a plaster for %0a%3c the iliac regions: it is curative also of prurigo, but it must %0a%3c never be administered in fevers. Taken in drink, it is a pre¬ %0a%3c ventive of sea sickness; and, worn attached to the body, %0a%3c beneath an apron, it arrests inguinal swellings. The smell of %0a%3c it 2 induces sleep, a similar effect being produced by placing %0a%3c it under the pillow unknown to the party. Kept among %0a%3c clothes it preserves them from worms, and used as a liniment, %0a%3c with oil, or burnt as a fumigation, it has the effect of driving %0a%3c away gnats. %0a%3c %0a%3c Writing ink, mixed with an infusion of wormwood, effectually %0a%3c protects the writings from the attacks of mice. Ashes of %0a%3c wormwood, mixed with rose unguent, stain the hair black. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 29.-ABSINTHIUM MAEINUM OK SEKIPHUH. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is a sea wormwood 3 also, known as “ seriplium” by %0a%3c some, the most esteemed being that of Taposiris in Egypt. %0a%3c Those initiated in the mysteries of Isis carry a branch of it in %0a%3c the hand. It lias a narrower leaf than the preceding plant, %0a%3c and is not so bitter; it is injurious to the stomach, has a %0a%3c laxative effect upon the bowels, and expels intestinal worms. %0a%3c It is taken in drink with oil and salt; or else an infusion of it %0a%3c is taken in a pottage made of meal of three-month wheat. %0a%3c When employed as a decoction, a handful is used to one sexta- %0a%3c rius of water, the mixture being boiled down to one half. %0a%3c %0a%3c 2 This, Fee observes, is not the case. %0a%3c %0a%3c 3 The Artemisia marilima of Linnaeus, Sea wormwood : see B. xxxii. %0a%3c C. 31. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 236 pliny’s natural history. [BookXXVIl. %0a%3c %0a%3c C1TAP. 30. (8.)- THE BALLOTES, MELAMPRASION, OR BLACK LEEK: %0a%3c %0a%3c THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Greeks give to the ballotes 1 the other name of “ melam¬ %0a%3c prasion,” meaning “black leek.’’’ It is a branchy plant, with %0a%3c black angular stems, covered with hairy leaves, larger and darker %0a%3c than those of the leek, 6 and possessed of a powerful smell. The %0a%3c leaves, bruised and applied with salt, are highly efficacious lor %0a%3c bites inflicted bv dogs : cooked upon hot ashes and applied in %0a%3c a cabbage leaf, they are curative of condylomata. Mixed with %0a%3c honey, this plant acts as a detergent upon sordid ulcers. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 31. -BOTRYS, AMBROSIA, OR ARTEMISIA: ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c Botrys 7 is a shrublike plant, which has small yellow %0a%3c branches, with the seed growing all round them, and leaves %0a%3c resembling 8 those of endive. It is found upon the banks oi %0a%3c running streams, and is used for the cure of hardness of %0a%3c breathing. The people of Cappadocia call this plant “ am¬ %0a%3c brosia,” others again, “ artemisia.” %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 32. -THE BRABYLA : ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c The brabyla 9 is possessed of astringent properties like those %0a%3c of the quince, but beyond this, authors give no particulars %0a%3c relative to it. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 33. -BHYON MARITIMUM : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Sea bryon 10 is a plant, no doubt , 11 with leaves like those of %0a%3c %0a%3c 4 The Eallota nigra of Linnaeus, the Fetid hallota, or Stinking black %0a%3c horehound; see B. xx. c. 89. %0a%3c %0a%3c 5 He is in error here, as the word “melamprasion” means “black %0a%3c horehound.’’ “ Black leek ” would be “ melamprason.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 6 “Horehound,” properly. The Ballota is of a stimulating nature, and %0a%3c contains a considerable quantity of essential oil. %0a%3c %0a%3c 7 The Chenopodium botrys of Linnaeus, Cut-leaved goose foot, or oak %0a%3c of Jerusalem. See B. xxv. c. 36, and c. 11 of this Book. %0a%3c %0a%3c 8 There is no such resemblance. The name “ botrys ” was given to %0a%3c the plant from the little clusters formed by the blossoms. %0a%3c %0a%3c 9 Identified by Fee with the Prunus domestica of Linnaeus, var. /3, or %0a%3c Damascena, the Damascene plum or damson. Desfontaines considers it %0a%3c to be the Prunus instititia, the Bullace plum. Holland mentions in a Note, %0a%3c “ Bullois, skegs, or such like wild plums.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 10 The Ulva lactuca of Linnaeus, Lettuce laver; see B. xiii. c. 49, B. %0a%3c xxiv. c. 17, and B. xxxii. c. 36. %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 He probably says this in reference to the opinion expressed by Theo- %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap 35.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE CATANAMCE. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 237 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c the lettuce, of a wrinkled, pursed appearance, and destitute of %0a%3c stem, the leaves arising from a single root: it grows upon %0a%3c rocks more particularly, and shells sunk in the sand. It ha3 %0a%3c desiccative 12 and astringent qualities in a very high degree, %0a%3c properties which render it useful for reducing all kinds of %0a%3c abscesses and inflammations, those attendant upon gout in %0a%3c particular. It is good also for all affections which stand in %0a%3c need of cooling applications. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 34. -THE BUPLEURON : ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c I find it stated that seed of bupleuron 13 is given for injuries %0a%3c inflicted by serpents ; and that the wound is fomented with %0a%3c a decoction of the plant, in combination with leaves of the %0a%3c mulberry or of origanum . 14 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 35. —THE CATANANCE ; ONE OBSERVATION UPON IT. THE %0a%3c CEMOS I ONE OBSERVATION UPON IT. %0a%3c %0a%3c The catanance 15 is a Thessalian plant, which it would be %0a%3c a mere loss of time to describe, seeing that it is only used as %0a%3c an ingredient in philtres. In order, however, to expose the %0a%3c follies of the magical art, it may not be out of place to remark %0a%3c that this plant has been selected for the above-named purpose, %0a%3c from the fact that, as it withers, it gradually contracts and %0a%3c assumes the shape of the claws of a dead kite . 16 %0a%3c %0a%3c For a similar reason we shall give no description of the %0a%3c plant called “ cemos .” 17 %0a%3c %0a%3c pbrastus, Hist. iv. 7, that it was a name for sea-weed in general, and not %0a%3c u specific plant. %0a%3c %0a%3c In reality, it is destitute of medicinal properties. Some kinds of laver %0a%3c are considered a dainty food. %0a%3c %0a%3c 13 See B. xxii. c. 35. 14 See B. xx. c. 67. %0a%3c %0a%3c 15 Dioscorides speaks of two kinds of Catanance ; one of which has %0a%3c been identified hy Sprengel with the Ornithopus compressus of Linnaeus, %0a%3c and the other with the Astragalus pugniformis. Fee expresses his doubts %0a%3c as to the correctness of these conclusions. %0a%3c %0a%3c |r> “ As if it would catch women, and hold them fast perforce.”— Holland. %0a%3c It has been suggested that the Coronopus, or “ crow’s foot,” mentioned %0a%3c in B. xxi. c. 59, was so called for a similar reason. %0a%3c %0a%3c II Prosper Alpinus identifies it with the Flantago Cretica of Linnaeus, %0a%3c and Sprengel with the Micropus erectus of Linnaeus. Fee considers it to %0a%3c be the Gnaphalium lcontopodium of Lamarck. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 238 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c plixy’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 36. —THE CALYX : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Of the calyx 18 there are two kinds. One of these resembles %0a%3c arum, and is found growing in ploughed soils; the proper %0a%3c time for gathering it being before it begins to wither. It is em¬ %0a%3c ployed for the same purposes as arum ; 19 and an infusion of the %0a%3c root is taken as a purgative and as an emmenagogue. The %0a%3c stalks, boiled with the leaves and some pulse, are curative of %0a%3c tenesmus. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 37. -THE CALYX, KNOWN ALSO AS ANCHUSA OR ONOCLIA : %0a%3c %0a%3c TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The other 20 kind of calyx is known by some persons as %0a%3c “ anchusa,” and by others as “ onoclia.” The leaves are like %0a%3c those of the lettuce, but longer, and with a downy surface. %0a%3c The root is red, and is employed topically, in combination %0a%3c with fine polenta , 21 for the cure of erysipelas: taken inter¬ %0a%3c nally with white wine, it is good for affections of the liver. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 38. -THE CIRCAEA : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The circaea 22 resembles the cultivated trychnon 23 in ap¬ %0a%3c pearance. It has a small swarthy flower, a diminutive seed, %0a%3c like millet, growing in small horn-shaped pods, and a root %0a%3c half a foot in length, generally triple or fourfold, white, %0a%3c odoriferous, and hot in the mouth. It is found growing upon %0a%3c rocks exposed to the sun. An infusion of it is prepared with %0a%3c wine, and administered for pains and affections of the uterus: %0a%3c to make it, three ounces of the pounded root should be steeped %0a%3c %0a%3c 18 Other readings are “calsa, ” and “calla;” but “calyx” is supported %0a%3c by the text of Dioscorides, B. iv. c. 23. The first kind has been generally %0a%3c identified with the Arum arisarum of Linnaeus, Hooded arum, or Honk’s %0a%3c hood, and is identical probably with the Aris aros of B. xxiv. c. 94. %0a%3c %0a%3c 19 See B. xxiv. c. 93. %0a%3c %0a%3c 20 Probably the Anchusa tinctoria of Linnaeus, Dyer’s alkanet. See B. %0a%3c xxii. c. 23. %0a%3c %0a%3c 21 “ Flore polentae.” See B. xviii. c. 14. %0a%3c %0a%3c 22 Sprengel identifies it with the Asclepias nigra, Black swallow-wort, %0a%3c %0a%3c but Fee considers it to be the Circaea Lutetiana of Linnaeus, Parisian %0a%3c circaea, or enchanter’s nightshade. Other authorities have suggested the %0a%3c Capsicum annuum of Linnaeus, Indian or Guinea pepper, and the Celosia %0a%3c margaritacea of Linnaeus, Pearly celosia, or cock's comb. M. Fraas %0a%3c suggests, though with some doubt, the Cynanchum Monspeliacum, the %0a%3c Mwitpellier dog’s-bane. 23 gee 3 xx i. c ^5 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 40.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE CBAT^GONON. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 239 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c in three sextarii of wine a day and a night. This potion is %0a%3c effectual also for bringing away the after-birth. The seed of %0a%3c this plant, taken in wine or hydromel, diminishes the milk in %0a%3c nursing women. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 39.- THE CIBSION : ONE BEMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c The cirsion 24 is a plant consisting of a diminutive and deli¬ %0a%3c cate stem, two cubits in height, of a triangular form, and %0a%3c covered with prickly leaves. The prickles on the leaves are %0a%3c downy, and the leaves themselves resemble those of buglos- %0a%3c sos 25 in shape, but are smaller, and of a whitish colour. At %0a%3c the summit of the plant there are small purple heads, which %0a%3c fall off in the shape of down. This plant or the root of it, %0a%3c worn as an amulet, it is said, is curative of the pains attendant %0a%3c upon varicose veins. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 40.- THE cuat^gonon; two kinds of it : EIGHT %0a%3c %0a%3c BEJIEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The crataegonon 20 is similar to an ear of corn in appearance. %0a%3c It is formed of numerous shoots, springing from a single root, %0a%3c and full of joints. It grows in umbrageous localities, and has %0a%3c a seed like that of millet, with a remarkably acrid taste. If %0a%3c a man and woman, before the evening meal, take three oboli of %0a%3c this seed in three cyathi of water, for forty days consecutively, %0a%3c before the conception of their issue, it will be sure to be of the %0a%3c male 27 sex, they say. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is another crataegonon, known also as “ thelygonos,” 2 ® %0a%3c and distinguished from the last mentioned plant by the mild¬ %0a%3c ness of the taste. Some persons assert that females, if they %0a%3c take the blossom of this plant in drink, will be sure to con¬ %0a%3c ceive before the end of forty days. These plants, used in com¬ %0a%3c bination with honey, are curative of black ulcers of a chronic %0a%3c nature; they also fill the concavities made by fistulous %0a%3c %0a%3c 24 Identified with the Carduus parvifloras of Linnaeus, the Small-flowered %0a%3c thistle. 25 See B. xxv. c. 40. %0a%3c %0a%3c 26 Identified by Fee and Desfontaines with the Polygonum persicaria of %0a%3c Linnaeus, the Spotted persicaria, red-shanks, fleawort, or lakeweed. Littre %0a%3c gives the Crucianella Monspeliaca of Linnaeus, Montpellier petty madder. %0a%3c %0a%3c 27 Hence its name, signifying that it strengthens the generative powers. %0a%3c %0a%3c M See B. xxvi. c. 91. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 240 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINY’S NATURAL HISTORY. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ulcers with new flesh, and restore such parts of the body as %0a%3c are wasted by atrophy. They act as a detergent upon purulent %0a%3c sores, disperse inflammatory tumours, and alleviate gout and %0a%3c all kind of abscesses, those of the mamillae in particular. %0a%3c %0a%3c Under the name of “ crataegos ” 29 or %3c%3c cratoegon,” Theo¬ %0a%3c phrastus 30 speaks of the tree known in Italy as the “ aquifolia." %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 41. -THE CROCOD1LEON : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The crocodileon 31 resembles the black chamoeleon 32 in shape: %0a%3c the root is long, of an uniform thickness, and possessed of a %0a%3c pungent smell. It is found growing in sandy soils. Taken %0a%3c in drink, it causes a copious discharge of coagulated blood at %0a%3c the nostrils, and in this way, it is said, diminishes the volume %0a%3c of the spleen. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 42. -THE CYNOSORCHIS OR ORCHIS : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The cynosorchis , 33 by some called “ orchis,” has leaves like 14 %0a%3c those of the olive, soft, three in number, half a foot in length, %0a%3c and lying upon the ground. The root is bulbous, oblong, and %0a%3c divided into two portions , 35 the upper one hard, and the lower %0a%3c one soft. These roots are eaten boiled, like bulbs , 38 and are %0a%3c mostly found growing in vineyards. If males eat the upper %0a%3c part, they will be parents of male issue, they .say, and females, %0a%3c if they eat the lower part, of female. In Thessaly, the men %0a%3c take the soft portion in goats’ milk as an aphrodisiac, and the %0a%3c hard part as an antaphrodisiac. Of these parts, the one effec¬ %0a%3c tually neutralizes the action of the other . 31 %0a%3c %0a%3c 29 See B. xxiv. c. 72. Littre remarks that Pliny is in error here, for %0a%3c that the Cratsegos of Theophrastus is the Cratsegos azarolia of Linnaeus, %0a%3c the Parsley-leaved hawthorn, while the Aquifolia of Pliny is the Holly. %0a%3c As to the latter point, see B. xvi. cc. 8, 12. %0a%3c %0a%3c 30 Hist. Plant. B. iii. c. 15. %0a%3c %0a%3c 31 Desfontaines identifies it with the Centaurea crocodileum of Linnaeus, %0a%3c %0a%3c and Littre with the Carduus pycnocephalus of Linnaeus. Ruellius con¬ %0a%3c siders it to be the same plant as the Leucacantha of Dioscorides, which %0a%3c Sprengel identifies with the Cnicus Casabonse. Fee expresses himself at %0a%3c a loss as to its identity. 32 See B. xxii. c. 21. %0a%3c %0a%3c 33 “ Dog’s testicle.” Considered to be a synonym merely of the Orchis, %0a%3c mentioned in B. xxvi. c. 62. 34 This comparison is totally incorrect. %0a%3c %0a%3c 35 See B. xxvi. c. 62. 3 « Or onions. %0a%3c %0a%3c 31 A tissue of groundless superstitions. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 44.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE C0CUBALUS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 241 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 43. —THE CHRYSOLACHANUM ; TWO VARIETIES OF IT : %0a%3c %0a%3c THKEE IiEMEDIES. COAGULCM TERIUS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The chrysolachanum 38 grows in pine plantations, and is %0a%3c similar to the lettuce in appearance. It heals wounds of the %0a%3c sinews, if applied without delay. There is another kind 39 of %0a%3c chrysolachanum mentioned, with a golden flower, and a leaf %0a%3c like that of the cabbage : it is boiled and eaten as a laxative %0a%3c vegetable. This plant, worn as an amulet by a patient suffer¬ %0a%3c ing from jaundice, provided it be always kept in sight, is a cure %0a%3c for that disease, it is said. 1 am not certain whether this is %0a%3c all that might be said about the chrysolachanum, but, at %0a%3c all events, it is all that I have found respecting it; for it is %0a%3c a very general fault on the part of our more recent herbalists, %0a%3c to confine their account of plants to the mere name, with a %0a%3c very meagre description of the peculiar features of the plant, %0a%3c —just as though, forsooth, they were universally known. Thus, %0a%3c they tell us, for instance, that a plant known as “ coagulum 40 %0a%3c terra,” acts astringently upon the bowels, and that it dispels %0a%3c strangury, taken in water or in wflne. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAI*. 44. —THE CCCUBALTJS, ST RUM US, OR STRYCHNON : SIX %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The leaves of the cucubalus, 41 they tell us, bruised with %0a%3c vinegar, are curative of the stings of serpents and of scorpions. %0a%3c Some persons call this plant by the name of “ strumus,” 42 %0a%3c while others give it the Greek name of “ strychnon its ber¬ %0a%3c ries are black. The juice of these berries, administered in %0a%3c doses of one cyathus, in two cyathi of honied wine, is-curative %0a%3c of lumbago ; an infusion of them with rose oil is used for head¬ %0a%3c ache, and they are employed as an application for scrofulous %0a%3c 6ores. %0a%3c %0a%3c M “ Golden vegetable.” Supposed to be identical with the Atriplex of %0a%3c B. xx. c. 38, our Orage. %0a%3c %0a%3c M Cultivated orage, probably. %0a%3c %0a%3c 40 “Earth rennet.” This plant has not been identified. Lobelius lias %0a%3c made a guess at the Serapias ahprtiva of Linnaeus, the Helleborine. It is %0a%3c pretty clear that it was unknown to Pliny himself. %0a%3c %0a%3c 41 The same, probably, as the Trychnon of B. xxi. cc. 52,105, Solanum %0a%3c nigrum or Black nightshade. In the former editions the reading is “cuculus.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 42 The “strumous” or “scrofula” plant. %0a%3c %0a%3c VOL. T. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c U %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 2-12 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 45. —THE CONFERVA : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The conferva 43 is peculiar to running streams, those of the %0a%3c Alpine regions more particularly; receiving its name from %0a%3c “ conferrumino,” 44 to solder together. Properly speaking, it is %0a%3c rather a fresh-water sponge than a moss or a plant, being a %0a%3c dense, porous mass of filaments. I know an instance where a %0a%3c man, who fell to the ground while lopping a tree of consider¬ %0a%3c able height, and broke nearly every bone of his body, was cured %0a%3c by the agency of this plant. The patient’s body was covered all %0a%3c over with conferva, the application being continually sprinkled %0a%3c with water the moment it began to dry, and only removed for %0a%3c the purpose of changing it when the plant gave signs of losing %0a%3c its virtues. 45 It is hardly credible with what rapidity he re¬ %0a%3c covered. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 46. (9.)— THE COCCUS CNIDIUS, OR GRAIN OF CNIDOS: TWO %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Cnidian grain 46 has just the colour of the kermes berry. 4 ’ %0a%3c It is larger than a peppercorn, and has very heating proper¬ %0a%3c ties : hence it is that when used, it is taken in crumb of %0a%3c bread, that it may not burn the throat in passing downwards. %0a%3c It is a sovereign remedy for hemlock, and arrests 48 looseness of %0a%3c the bowels. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 47. -THE DIPSACOS : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The dipsacos 49 has leaves like those of the lettuce, witli %0a%3c prickly tubercles on the middle of the back. The stem of it, %0a%3c two cubits in length, is bristling all over with prickles of a %0a%3c similar nature. The joints of the stem are closely covered %0a%3c with two leaves, which form a concave axil in which a saltish %0a%3c dew-like liquid collects. 50 At the summit of the stem there %0a%3c %0a%3c 43 Possibly the Conferva rivularis, or the C. glomerata of Linnaeus, the %0a%3c River conferva or River sponge, or the Green cluster conferva. %0a%3c %0a%3c 44 On account of its asserted agglutinative properties. In reality it is %0a%3c an inert plant, and is never used in medicine. %0a%3c %0a%3c 45 Fee considers this statement as fabulous in every respect. %0a%3c %0a%3c 46 See B. xiii. c. 35. %0a%3c %0a%3c 47 “Coccus.” See B. xvi. c. 12. %0a%3c %0a%3c 48 This is not the case. Sillig is of opinion that the passage is imperfect. %0a%3c %0a%3c 49 The same plant as the Labrum Venereum of B. xxv. c. 108. It is %0a%3c used for carding cloth, but is no longer employed in medicine. %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 Hence its name “ Venus’ bath.” %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 50.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE ELATESTE. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 243 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c are small heads covered with prickles: it grows in watery %0a%3c localities. %0a%3c %0a%3c This plant is used for the cure of chaps of the fundament %0a%3c and of fistula; in which latter case the root is boiled down in %0a%3c wine to the consistency of wax, to allow of its being introduced %0a%3c into the fistula in the form of a salve. 51 It is employed, too, %0a%3c for the cure of all .kinds of warts: as a liniment for which, %0a%3c the juice collected in the axils, as above mentioned, is also used %0a%3c by some. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 48. -THE DBYOPTEB1S : TWO BEMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The dryopteris, 62 which resembles fern in appearance, is %0a%3c found growing upon trees; the leaves are of a somewhat sweet¬ %0a%3c ish 43 flavour and marked with slight indentations, and the %0a%3c root is hairy. This plant is possessed of caustic properties, 51 %0a%3c and hence the root is pounded and used as a depilatory. In %0a%3c using it the skin is rubbed with it till perspiration is excited, %0a%3c the operation being repeated a second and a third time, care %0a%3c being taken not to remove the perspiration. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 49. -THE DBYOPHONON. %0a%3c %0a%3c The dryophonon 65 is a similar plant, with thin stems a cubit %0a%3c in length, and surrounded on either side with leaves about as %0a%3c large as the thumb and like those of the oxymyrsine 56 in ap¬ %0a%3c pearance, only whiter and softer: the blossom is white, and %0a%3c similar to that of the elder. The shoots of it are eaten boiled, %0a%3c aud the seed is used as a substitute for pepper. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 50.- THE ELATENE : TWO BEMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The elatine 57 has leaves like those of the helxine, 58 diminu- %0a%3c %0a%3c 41 “ Collyrii.” %0a%3c %0a%3c w The same plant, probably, as tbe Polypodion of B. xxvi. c. 37. Littre, %0a%3c however, identifies it with tbe Asplenium adiantum nigrum of Linnaeus, the %0a%3c Black maiden-hair, or spleenwort. %0a%3c %0a%3c 53 It is the root that is sweet, and not the leaves. %0a%3c %0a%3c 44 It has no such properties. %0a%3c %0a%3c 54 The “ oak-killer.” Fee thinks that it may possibly be tbe Conval- %0a%3c laria uniflora of Linnaeus. Desfontaines names the Coehlearia draba, and %0a%3c Littre the Lepidium draba of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 46 See B. xv. cc. 7, 37, and B. xxiii. c. 83. %0a%3c %0a%3c 47 Desfontaines and Fee identify it with the Antirrhinum spurium of %0a%3c %0a%3c Linmeus, Bastard toad-flax, calves’ snout, or snapdragon. Littre gives %0a%3c the Linaria Gneca as its synonym. 58 See B. xxii. c. 19. %0a%3c %0a%3c n 2 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 244 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c tive, round, and hairy; its branches are small, half a foot in %0a%3c length, five or six in number, and covered with leaves from %0a%3c the root upwards. It grows in corn-fields, and has a rough %0a%3c flavour: hence it is found very useful for defluxions of the %0a%3c eyes, the leaves being beaten up and applied with polenta" in %0a%3c a liuen pledget. A decoction of this plant with linseed, taken %0a%3c in pottage, is good for dysentery. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 51. -EMTETROS, BY OUR PEOPLE CALLED CALCIFRAOA : FOUR %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Empetros, 60 by the people of our country called “calci- %0a%3c fraga,” 61 grows on mountains near the sea, and is generally %0a%3c found upon rocks: the nearer it grows to the sea the suiter it %0a%3c is, acting as an evacuant of bile and pituitous secretions. That, %0a%3c on the other hand, which grows at a greater distance and more %0a%3c inland, is of a more bitter flavour. It carries off the aqueous %0a%3c humours of the body, being taken for that purpose in broth of %0a%3c some kind, or else hydromel. When old, it loses its strength; %0a%3c but used fresh, either boiled in water or pounded, it acts as a %0a%3c diuretic, and disperses urinary calculi. Authorities who wish %0a%3c full credence to be given to this asserted property, assure us %0a%3c that pebbles boiled with it will split asunder. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 52. —THE EPIPACTIS OR ELLEBORINE : TW'O REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The epipactis, 6 ' 2 called “ elleborine ” by some, is a diminutive %0a%3c plant with small leaves. Taken in drink, it is extremely use¬ %0a%3c ful for diseases of the liver, and as an antidote to poisons. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 53.- THE EPIMEDION : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The epimedion 63 consists of a stem of moderate size, with %0a%3c ten or twelve leaves like those of ivy: it never flowers, and %0a%3c %0a%3c 59 See B. xviii. c. 14. %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 Fee, with Sprengel, identifies it with the Salsola polychlonos of Lin¬ %0a%3c naeus, Branchy saltwort or glasswort; Bauhin with the Passerina poly- %0a%3c galifolia. The Crithmum maritimum of Linnaeus, Sea samphire, has %0a%3c been suggested by Desfontaines. Littre gives the Frankenia pulverulcnta %0a%3c of Linnaeus. Holland suggests Saxifrage. %0a%3c %0a%3c 51 “ Calculus-breaking.” 62 See B. xiii. c. 35. %0a%3c %0a%3c 63 Sprengel suggests the Marsilea quadrifolia of Linnaeus; Cohimna %0a%3c the Botrychium lunaria of Linnaeus ; C. Bauhin the Ornithogalum Nar- %0a%3c bonense of Linnaeus, Narbonese star of Bethlehem ; and Talius the Caltha %0a%3c palustris of Linnaeus, the Marsh marigold. Fee considers its identification %0a%3c impossi ble. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 55.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c FILTX OK FERN. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 245 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c has a thin, black root, with a powerful smell. It grows in %0a%3c humid soils. This plant also has certain astringent and cool¬ %0a%3c ing properties, but females must be on their guard 61 against %0a%3c it. The leaves, beaten up in wine, prevent the bosom from %0a%3c growing too large in young girls. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 54. -THE ENNEAPHYLLON : TWO REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The enneaphyllon 65 has nine long leaves, and is of a caustic %0a%3c nature. It is employed topically, but 'when used it is wrapped %0a%3c in wool to prevent it from cauterizing further than desirable, %0a%3c for it blisters immediately. For lumbago and sciatica it is of %0a%3c the greatest utility. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAr. 55.— TWO VARIETIES OF FILIX OR FERN, KNOWN TO THE %0a%3c %0a%3c GREEKS AS PTERIS, OR BLACHNON, AND AS THELYPTERIS, OR %0a%3c %0a%3c NYMPHO PTERIS : ELEVEN REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Of fern there are two varieties, equally destitute of blossom %0a%3c and of seed. 66 The Greeks give the name of “pteris,” and %0a%3c sometimes “ blachnon,” to the kind 67 in which numerous shoots %0a%3c take their rise from a single root, exceeding two cubits even in %0a%3c length, and with a not unpleasant smell : 68 this plant is thought %0a%3c to be the male fern. %0a%3c %0a%3c The other kind is known to the Greeks as “ thelypteris,” 69 %0a%3c and sometimes, “ nymphoea pteris it has a single stem only, %0a%3c with comparatively few branches, is shorter, softer, and more %0a%3c tufted than the other, and has channelled leaves growing near %0a%3c the root. Swine are fattened upon the roots of either kind. %0a%3c The leaves of both kinds are arranged on either side in the %0a%3c form of wings, whence the Greek name “ pteris.” The roots %0a%3c are long, run obliquely, and are of a swarthy colour, more par- %0a%3c %0a%3c 64 Because it was said to be a cause of sterility. %0a%3c %0a%3c M Identified with the Dentaria enneaphylla of Linnaeus, the Nine-leaved %0a%3c tooth-wort. %0a%3c %0a%3c 66 From this remark, Fee is of opinion that he had in view more par¬ %0a%3c ticularly the Pteris aquilina and the Blechnum spicatum of Linnaeus, plants %0a%3c in which the seed is not easily detected. %0a%3c %0a%3c 67 Identified by Fee with the Polypodium filix mas of Linnaeus, the Male %0a%3c fern. %0a%3c %0a%3c 60 Dioscorides says it has a somewhat unpleasant smell, and this is nearer %0a%3c the truth. %0a%3c %0a%3c 69 “ Female fern.” Identified by Fee with the Polypodium filix faemina %0a%3c of Linnaeus, Female fern or Pteris aquilina. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 246 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Hook xxvir. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ticularly when dried : when wanted for use, they should be %0a%3c dried in the sun. These plants are found growing everywhere, %0a%3c but in cold soils more particularly; they should be taken up, %0a%3c too, at the setting of the Vergiliac. 70 The root is only used at the %0a%3c end of three years, neither before that period nor after. They %0a%3c act as an expellent of intestinal worms ; for tapeworm' 1 honey %0a%3c is taken with them, but in other cases sweet wine, for three days. %0a%3c %0a%3c They are, both of them, extremely detrimental to the sto¬ %0a%3c mach, but are laxative to the bowels, carrying off first the bile %0a%3c and then the aqueous humours of the body. When used for %0a%3c tapeworm, it is the best plan to take scammony with them, in %0a%3c equal proportions. For rheumatic defluxions, the root is taken %0a%3c in doses of two oboli, in water, after a day’s abstinence from %0a%3c food, a little honey being taken first. Neither kind must ever %0a%3c be given to females ; for in pregnancy they are productive of %0a%3c abortion, and in other cases entail sterility. Powdered fern is %0a%3c sprinkled upon sordid ulcers, as also upon the necks of beasts %0a%3c of burden, when chafed. Fern-leaves kill bugs, and serpents %0a%3c will never harbour among them : hence it is a good plan to %0a%3c strew them in places where the presence of those reptiles is %0a%3c suspected. The very smell, too, of burnt fern will put serpents %0a%3c to flight. Medical men have made this distinction as to ferns; %0a%3c that of Macedonia, they say, is the best, and that of Cassiope %0a%3c the next. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 56. —FEMUR BUBULUM, OR OX THIGH. %0a%3c %0a%3c The name of femur bubulum 72 is given to a plant which is %0a%3c good for the sinews, applied fresh, and beaten up with salt and %0a%3c vinegar. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 57. -GALEOPSIS, GALEOBDOLON, OR GALION : SIX REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Galeopsis, 73 or as some call it, “ galeobdolon” or “galion,” %0a%3c %0a%3c 70 See B. xviii. c. 59. %0a%3c %0a%3c 71 Fee remarks that root of fern is an undoubted remedy for tapeworm, %0a%3c and that it is worthy of remark that we owe to the ancients the two most %0a%3c efficient anthelmintics known, fern-root, namely, and pomegranate rind. %0a%3c %0a%3c 72 The Femur bubulum has not been identified. C. Bauhin has suggested %0a%3c the Leonurus cardiaca of Linnaeus, Motherwort. %0a%3c %0a%3c 13 It has been suggested that this plant is the same as the Laminin, %0a%3c mentioned in B. xxii. c. 16, but Fee is not of that opinion. He identifies %0a%3c the Galeopsis with the Lamium purpureum of Linnaeus, the Purple arch¬ %0a%3c angel, or dead-nettle. Littre gives as its synonym the Scrofularia pere- %0a%3c grina of Linnaeus, the Foreign figwort. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 59.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c GLAUCION. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 247 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c is a plant with a stem and leaves like those of the nettle, only- %0a%3c smaller ; and which, when bruised, emit a powerful smell. The %0a%3c flower is purple, and the plant is found growing everywhere, %0a%3c about hedges and foot-paths. The leaves and stems, bruised in %0a%3c vinegar, and applied topically, are curative of indurations, %0a%3c carcinomata, and scrofulous sores. They disperse also inflam¬ %0a%3c matory tumours and imposthumes of the parotid glands, and %0a%3c it is found a useful plan to foment the parts affected with a %0a%3c decoction of them. Applied with salt, this plant is curative %0a%3c of putrid ulcers and gangrenous sores. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 58.- THE GLAUX : ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c The glaux 74 was known in ancient times as the “ eugalac- %0a%3c ton.” 75 In the leaves it resembles the cytisus and the lentil, %0a%3c only that they are