 “ diaglaucia,” to medical men. The milk, when the secretion %0a%3c of it is stopped, is restored by the agency of this plant, for which %0a%3c purpose it is taken in water. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 60.— THE GLYCYS1DE, P^ONIA, OR rENTOROBOS : TWENTY %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The glycyside, 79 by some called “ pseonia” or “ pentorobos,” %0a%3c has a stem two cubits in length, accompanied by two or three %0a%3c others, and of a reddish colour, with a bark like that of the %0a%3c laurel. The leaves are similar to those of isatis, 80 but more %0a%3c unctuous, rounder, and more diminutive; the seed is enclosed %0a%3c in capsules, some being red and some black, there being %0a%3c two varieties of the plant. The female plant is generally %0a%3c thought to be the one to the root of which some six or eight %0a%3c bulbs are attached, of an elongated form; those of the male %0a%3c plant 61 being more in number, as it throws out more roots than %0a%3c one, a palm in length, and of a white colour : it has also an %0a%3c astringent taste. The leaves of the female plant smell like %0a%3c myrrh, 83 and lie closer together than those of the male. %0a%3c %0a%3c Both plants grow in the woods, and they should always be %0a%3c taken up at night, 83 it is said; as it would be dangerous to do %0a%3c so in the day-time, the woodpecker of Mars being sure to %0a%3c attack the eyes 94 of the person so engaged. It is stated also %0a%3c that the person, while taking up the root, runs great risk of %0a%3c being attacked with procidence of the anus : all this, however, %0a%3c I take to be so much fiction, most frivolously invented to puff %0a%3c off their supposed marvellous properties. Both plants are used 85 %0a%3c for various purposes: the red seed, taken in red wine, about %0a%3c fifteen in number, arrest menstruation ; while the black seed, %0a%3c taken in the same proportion, in either raisin or other wine, %0a%3c are curative of diseases of the uterus. The root, taken in wine, %0a%3c allay