ates gives the name of “ gallidraga” 88 to a plant %0a%3c which resembles the leucacanthus, 89 and grows in the marshes. %0a%3c It is a prickly plant, with a tall, ferulaceous stem, surmounted %0a%3c with a head somewhat similar to an egg in appearance. When %0a%3c this head is growing, in summer, small worms, 90 he says, are %0a%3c generated, which are put away in a box for keeping, and are %0a%3c attached as an amulet, with bread, to the arm on the side on %0a%3c which tooth-ache is felt; indeed it is quite wonderful, he says, %0a%3c hoiv soon the pain is removed. These worms, however, are of %0a%3c no use after the end of a year, or in cases where they have been %0a%3c allowed to touch the ground. %0a%3c %0a%3c 86 “ Suppressionibus nocturnis.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 87 Sprengel identifies it with the Santolina maritima, Sea cudwort or %0a%3c cotton-weed. Fee considers its identification as doubtful. %0a%3c %0a%3c 68 Identified by Hardouin and Desfontaines with the Dipsacus pilosus of %0a%3c Linnaeus, the Shepherd’s rod, or small white teasel. Fee is doubtful on %0a%3c the subject. %0a%3c %0a%3c 69 See B. xxii. c. 18. 90 See B. xxv. c. 28. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 250 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINY’S NATURAL HI8TOBY. [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 63. —HOLCTJ9 OR AKI8TIS. %0a%3c %0a%3c Holcus 91 is a plant that grows in arid, stony, spots: it has an %0a%3c ear at the end of a fine stem, and looks like barley that has put %0a%3c forth again when cut. Attached to the head or around the arm, %0a%3c it extracts 92 spikes of corn adhering to the flesh; for which %0a%3c reason, some persons give it the name of “ aristis.” %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 64. -HYOSERIS I ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c Hyoseris 92 * resembles endive in appearance, but is a smaller %0a%3c plant, and rougher to the touch : pounded and applied to %0a%3c wounds, it heals them with remarkable rapidity. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 65. -THE HOLOSTEON : THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The holosteon, 93 so called by the Greeks by way of anti- %0a%3c phrasis, 94 (in the same way that they give the name of %0a%3c “sweet” 95 to the gall,) is a plant destitute of all hardness, of %0a%3c such extreme fineness as to resemble hairs in appearance, four %0a%3c fingers in length, and very similar to hay-grass. The leaves of it %0a%3c are narrow, and it has a rough flavour : it grows upon elevated %0a%3c spots composed of humus. Taken in wine, it is used for rup¬ %0a%3c tures and convulsions. It has the property, also, of closing %0a%3c wounds; indeed, if applied to pieces of meat it will solder %0a%3c them together. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 66.-THE HIPPOPHiESTON ! EIGHT REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The hippophaeston is one of those prickly plants which %0a%3c fullers 96 use in their coppers ; it has neither stem nor flower, %0a%3c %0a%3c 91 Identified with the Hordeum murinum of Linnaeus, and the same, %0a%3c most probably, as the Mouse barley of B. xxii. c. 6-5. %0a%3c %0a%3c 92 Whence its name, from the Greek e\kui, “to draw.” %0a%3c %0a%3c “Swine’s endive.” It is generally identified with the Centaurea %0a%3c nigra of Linnaeus; though, as Fee says, on very insufficient grounds, as %0a%3c the black centaury has but little similarity to endive. %0a%3c %0a%3c 93 The “ all-hone ” plant. Desfontaines identifies it with the Plantago %0a%3c coronopus of Linnaeus, the Buckshorn plantain; but Fee prefers the Plan¬ %0a%3c tago holostea of Lamarck, the Grass-leaved plantain. Littre names the %0a%3c llolosteum umbellatum. The Plantago albicans of Linnaeus has been also %0a%3c mentioned. %0a%3c %0a%3c 94 Because there is no hardness in it. 93 Td y\vKta. %0a%3c %0a%3c 96 See B. xxiv. c. 68. In B. xvi. c. 92, Fee identifies this plant with the %0a%3c Calcitrapa stellata of Lamarck. He also suggests that it may possibly be %0a%3c the second “ Hippophaes,” mentioned in B. xxii. c. 14. Desfontaines %0a%3c identifies it with the Cnicus stellatus, the Star-thistle. Littre gives as its %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE I80PYB0N. %0a%3c %0a