t, with leaves twice the size of those of rue, and %0a%3c small ligneous branches, about the thickness of a rush. It %0a%3c bears close to the leaves a sort of fine beard or spike, standing %0a%3c by itself, on the extremity of which there are small white stones, %0a%3c as round as a pearl, about the size of a chick-pea, and as hard as %0a%3c a pebble. These stones, 12 at the part where they adhere to %0a%3c the stalk, have a small cavity, and contain a seed within. %0a%3c %0a%3c This plant is found in Italy, no doubt, but that of Crete is %0a%3c the most esteemed. Among all the plants, there is none that %0a%3c I ever contemplated with greater admiration than this; so %0a%3c beauteous is the conformation, that it might be fancied that the %0a%3c hand of an artist 13 had arranged a row of lustrous pearls alter¬ %0a%3c nately among the leaves ; so exquisite too the nicety in thus %0a%3c making a stone to grow upon a plant! The authorities say %0a%3c that this is a creeping plant, and that it lies upon the ground ; %0a%3c but for my own part, I have only seen it when plucked, and %0a%3c not while growing. It is well known that these small stones, %0a%3c taken in doses of one drachma, in white wine, break and %0a%3c expel urinary calculi, 14 and are curative of strangury. In¬ %0a%3c deed, there is no plant that so instantaneously proclaims, at %0a%3c %0a%3c 10 Identified by Fee and Desfontaines with the Lithospermum officinale %0a%3c of Linnaeus, Gremil, gromwell, or stone-crop. Littre mentions the Lithos- %0a%3c permum tenuifiorum of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 “Jove’s wheat,” or the “plant of Hercules.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 12 This description applies to the variety of Gremil, known as the Coix %0a%3c lacryma of Linnaeus, Job’s tears, originally an Indian plant; but it may %0a%3c have been known in Italy in Pliny’s time. %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 A poor compliment to Nature, as Fee remarks. %0a%3c %0a%3c 14 It has in reality no medicinal properties to speak of; but its name, %0a%3c “