a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 259 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 91. -TI1E rOLTGONOS, POLYGONATOS, TEUTHALIS, CARCI- %0a%3c %0a%3c NETURON, CLEM A, OR MYRTOPETALOS, OTHERWISE KNOWN AS %0a%3c %0a%3c 8ANGUINAR1A OR ORIOS : FOUR VARIETIES OF IT : FORTY %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Greeks give the name of “ polygonos” 52 to the plant %0a%3c known to us as “ sanguinaria.” 53 It is but little elevated above, %0a%3c the ground, has leaves like those of rue, and resembles grass %0a%3c in appearance. The juice of it, injected into the nostrils, %0a%3c arrests haemorrhage : taken with wine, it has a similar effect %0a%3c upon bleeding at any other part of the body, as also spitting %0a%3c of blood. Those who distinguish several kinds of polygonos, %0a%3c make this to be the male 54 plant, and say that it is so called %0a%3c from the large number of seeds, or else from its numerous %0a%3c branches. Some call-it “ polygonatos,” 55 from the number of %0a%3c its joints, others, again, “ teuthalis,” and others, “ carcine- %0a%3c thron,” “ clema,” or “ myrtopetalos.” %0a%3c %0a%3c There are some authorities to be found, however, who say that %0a%3c this is the female plant, and that the male is more diminutive, %0a%3c less swarthy, and more jointed, with a seed protruding beneath %0a%3c all the leaves. However this may be, these plants are of an %0a%3c astringent, cooling nature. The seed is laxative, and, taken in %0a%3c large doses, acts as a diuretic, and arrests defluxions; indeed, %0a%3c if there is no defluxion, it is of no use taking it. Tor burning %0a%3c heats of the stomach, the leaves are applied topically ; and they %0a%3c are used, in the form of a liniment, for pains in the bladder, and %0a%3c for erysipelas. The juice is used as an injection for suppurations %0a%3c of the ears, and by itself, for pains in the eyes. It is admi¬ %0a%3c nistered, also, in fevers, tertian and quartan fevers more par¬ %0a%3c ticularly, in doses of two cyathi, just before the paroxysms %0a%3c come ou; as also in cases of cholera, dysentery, and derange¬ %0a%3c ment of the stomach. %0a%3c %0a%3c There is a third kind, which grows on the mountains, and is %0a%3c known as “orios,” 66 similar to a delicate reed in appearance, and %0a%3c %0a%3c 52 “ Many-seeded.” 53 “ Blood plant.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 54 Identified by Fee with the Polygonum aviculare of Linnaeus, the %0a%3c Knot-grass. %0a%3c %0a%3c w “Many-knotted.” Scribonius says that it received its name, “poly¬ %0a%3c gonos,” from its being found everywhere. %0a%3c %0a%3c 56 Or “ mountain ” plant. Fee considers it to be the same as the %0a%3c second kind above mentioned, and to correspond with the female Polygonos %0a%3c of Dioscorides. He identifies it with the Hippuris vulgaris of Linnaeus, %0a%3c %0a%3c s 2 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 260 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c PLINY’S natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c having but a single stem, with numerous joints running into %0a%3c one another; the leaves of it are similar to those of the pitch- %0a%3c tree, and the root is never used. This variety, however, is not %0a%3c so efficacious as those already mentioned, and, indeed, is used %0a%3c exclusively for sciatica. A fourth kind is known as the wild 17 %0a%3c polygonos : it is a shrub, almost a tree in fact, with a ligneous %0a%3c root, a red trunk like that of the cedar, and branches resem¬ %0a%3c bling those of spartum, 58 a couple of palms in length, and with %0a%3c three or four dark-coloured, knotted joints. This kind, also, is %0a%3c of an astringent nature, and has a flavour like that of the %0a%3c quince. It is either boiled down in water to one third, or else %0a%3c dried and powdered for sprinkling upon ulceratioriB of the %0a%3c mouth and excoriations: it is chewed, also, for affections of %0a%3c the gums. It arrests the progress of corrosive ulcers and of all %0a%3c sores of a serpiginous nature, or which cicatrize with difficulty, %0a%3c and is particularly useful for ulcerations caused by Bnow. %0a%3c Herbalists employ it also for quinzy, and use it as a chaplet for %0a%3c head-ache; for defluxions of the eyes, they put it round the %0a%3c neck. %0a%3c %0a%3c In cases of tertian fever, some persons pull it up wuth the %0a%3c left hand, and attach it as an amulet to the body; the same, %0a%3c too, in cases of haemorrhage. There is no plant that is more %0a%3c generally kept by them in a dry state than the polygonos. %0a%3c %0a%3c chap. 92. —the pancratium: twelve remedies. %0a%3c %0a%3c The pancratium is called by some the “little squill,” M in %0a%3c preference : it has leaves like those of the white lily, but %0a%3c longer and thicker, and a root composed of a large, red, bulb. %0a%3c The juice of it, taken with meal of fltches, relaxes the bowels, %0a%3c and acts as a detergent upon ulcers : for dropsy, and diseases %0a%3c of the spleen, it is administered with honey. Some persons %0a%3c boil it till the water becomes sweet; the water is then poured %0a%3c off, and the root is pounded and divided into tablets, which %0a%3c %0a%3c Mare’s tail, or female horse-tail; Littre gives the Equisetum pallidum of %0a%3c Bory as its synonym. %0a%3c %0a%3c 57 Identified by Fee with the Ephedra distachya of Linnaeus, the Great %0a%3c shrubby horsetail. %0a%3c %0a%3c 58 See B, xix. c. 7. %0a%3c %0a%3c 53 “ Scillam pusillam.” Fee considers it to be a squill, the variety with %0a%3c the red root of the Scilla maritima of Linnaeus, the Sea-squill. Littre %0a%3c gives as its synonym the Pancratium maritimum of Linnaeus, the Seu- %0a%3c daflbdil. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 94.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE PEKICLYMENOS. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 2G1 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c are dried in the sun and used for ulcerations of the head, and %0a%3c other affections which require detergents. It is sometimes %0a%3c given for cough, a pinch in three fingers in wine, and, in the %0a%3c form of an electuary, for pains in the side or peripneumony. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is administered, also, in wine, for sciatica, griping pains %0a%3c in the bowels, and retardations of the catamenia. %0a%3c %0a%3c CBAP. 93. —THE PEPLIS, SYCE, MECONIOH, OR MECON APHRODES: %0a%3c %0a%3c THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The peplis , 60 known by the various names of “ syce ,” 0 %0a%3c “ meconion,” and “ mecon aphrodes,” is a shrub- like plant, %0a%3c springing from a single, diminutive, root. The leaves of it %0a%3c resemble those of rue, but are a little larger; the seed, which %0a%3c lies beneath the leaves, is round, and smaller than that of the %0a%3c white poppy. It is ordinarily gathered in vineyards, at %0a%3c harvest-time, and is dried with the seed on, receivers being %0a%3c placed beneath to catch it as it falls. This seed, taken in drink, %0a%3c purges the bowels, and carries off bile andpituitous secretions: %0a%3c one acetabulum, taken in three heminae of hydromel, is a %0a%3c middling dose. It is sprinkled also upon meat and other articles %0a%3c of food, as a laxative medicine. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 94. —THE PE1UCLYMEN0S : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The periclymenos 62 is also a shrub-like plant, with two %0a%3c whitish, soft, leaves, arranged at intervals. At the extremity, %0a%3c among the leaves, is the seed, hard, and very difficult to %0a%3c pluck. It grows in ploughed fields and hedges, entwining %0a%3c around every object from which it can gain support. The seed %0a%3c is dried in the shade, pounded, and divided into lozenges. %0a%3c These lozenges are left to dissolve, in three cyathi of white %0a%3c wine, fora period of thirty days, and are given for diseases of %0a%3c the spleen ; the volume of which is gradually diminished either %0a%3c by discharges of bloody urine, or else by alvine evacuation, %0a%3c the effects of the medicament being perceptible at the end of %0a%3c ten days. The leaves, boiled, act as a diuretic, and are useful %0a%3c for hardness of breathing. Taken in drink, in manner above- %0a%3c %0a%3c 40 Probably the Euphorbia peplis of Linnaeus; see B. xx. c. 81. It is a %0a%3c strong purgative. %0a%3c %0a%3c ““Fig-plant,” “poppy-juice,” and “ poppy-froth.” In reference, %0a%3c no doubt, to its milky juice. %0a%3c %0a%3c 42 See the Clymenus, B. xxv. c. 33. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 262 plint’s natural history. [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c mentioned, they facilitate delivery, and bring away the after¬ %0a%3c birth. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 95. -PELECINON *. ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c We have already® spoken of pelecinon as growing in corn¬ %0a%3c fields, a plant which throws out a number of shoots from %0a%3c thin stems, and has leaves like those of the chick-pea. The %0a%3c seed, which is contained in pods of a curved shape, like %0a%3c diminutive horns and three or four in number, is similar to %0a%3c gith 61 in appearance, bitter, and an excellent stomachic. It is %0a%3c used as an ingredient in antidotes . 65 %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 96. -POLYGALA : ONE REMEDY. %0a%3c %0a%3c Polygala 66 is a palm in height, with leaves like those of the %0a%3c lentil at the extremity of the stem. It has an astringent taste; %0a%3c taken in drink, it increases the milk in nursing women. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 97. -POTERION, PHRYNION, OR NEURAS : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Poterion , 67 or, as some call it, “ phrynion” or “ neuras,”® %0a%3c throws out numerous branches, is shrivelled and prickly, and %0a%3c covered with a thick down. The leaves of it are small and %0a%3c round; the branches long, soft, thin, and flexible; and the %0a%3c blossom elongated, and of a grass-green colour. The seed is %0a%3c never used, but it has a pungent flavour and a powerful smell: %0a%3c the plant is found growing upon moist, watery, elevations. %0a%3c The roots are two or three in number, some two cubits in %0a%3c length, sinewy, white, and firm. It is dug up in autumn, and %0a%3c the stem yields a juice like gum, when cut. The root is said %0a%3c to be of wonderful efficacy as an application for the cure of %0a%3c wounds, more particularly of the sinews, even when severed. %0a%3c A decoction of it is also taken, with honey, for relaxations of %0a%3c the sinews, and for weakness or wounds of those parts. %0a%3c %0a%3c 63 In B. xviii. c. 44. It was also called “ securidaca.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 64 See B. xx. c. 71. %0a%3c %0a%3c 65 We learn from Galen that it formed an ingredient in the great anti¬ %0a%3c dote of Mithridates. %0a%3c %0a%3c 66 Fee thinks that it may possibly be the Polygala vulgaris of Linnaeus, the %0a%3c Common milk-wort. Desfontaines mentions the Polygala amara of Lin¬ %0a%3c naeus, the Bitter milkwort of the South of Europe; and Littre gives the %0a%3c Polygala venulosa of Sibthorp. %0a%3c %0a%3c 67 See B. xxv. c. 70. 66 The “ sinew ” plant. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 203 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 100.] THE PHTLLON. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 98. -THE PHALANGITIS, PHALANGION, Ofi LF.UCACANTHA : %0a%3c %0a%3c FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The phalangitis 69 is by some called “ phalangion,” and by %0a%3c others “ leucanthemum ,” 70 or, as I find it written in some %0a%3c copies, “ leucacantha .” 71 Its branches are diminutive, never %0a%3c less than two in number, and running in contrary directions : %0a%3c the blossom is white, and similar to the flower of the red lily ; %0a%3c the seed dark and broad, resembling the half of a lentil, but %0a%3c much thinner; and the root slender and of a grass-green colour. %0a%3c The leaves, blossoms, or seed of this plant are employed for %0a%3c the cure of wounds inflicted by Bcorpions, serpents, and the %0a%3c phalangium , 72 and for the removal of griping pains in the %0a%3c bowels. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 99. -THE PHYTEUMA : ONE PROPERTY'. %0a%3c %0a%3c As for the phyteuma , 73 I think it a mere loss of time to %0a%3c describe it, it being only used as an ingredient in philtres. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP 100. -THE PHYLLON : ONE PROPERTY. %0a%3c %0a%3c The Greeks give the name of “phyllon ” 74 td a plant which %0a%3c grows among the rocks, in mountainous spots. The female 