k and honey, in wine %0a%3c or vinegar, breaks urinary calculi, und is curative of diseases %0a%3c of the bladder. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 103. -THE POLYRRHIZON : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The polyrrhizon 79 has leaves like those of myrtle, and %0a%3c numerous roots. These roots are pounded and administered %0a%3c in wine, for injuries inflicted by serpents : they are useful, also, %0a%3c for cattle. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 104. -THE PHOSERPINACA : FIVE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The proserpinaca , 79 a common plant enough, is an excellent %0a%3c remedy for the sting of the scorpion. Powdered and mixed %0a%3c with brine and oil, in which the maena 80 has been preserved, it %0a%3c is an excellent cure, they say, for quinzy . 81 It is also stated %0a%3c that, however fatigued a person may be, to the extent even of %0a%3c losing his voice, he will be sure to be refreshed,., by putting this %0a%3c plant beneath his tongue ; and that if it is eaten, a vomit will %0a%3c be the result, productive of good effects. %0a%3c %0a%3c 78 Linn®us has given to the Fine-leaved water-hemlock the name of %0a%3c Phellandrium aquaticum, but the seeds of that plant are an active poison. %0a%3c It is probable that the Phellandrium, or “Male-cork-plant” of Pliny, %0a%3c still remains unknown. %0a%3c %0a%3c 76 Possibly the Phalaris aquatica of Linnaeus, the Water canary-grass. %0a%3c Littre gives as its synonym, the Phalaris nodosa of Linnaeus, Knotted %0a%3c canary-grass. See Beckmann, Hist. lnv. Vol. I. p. 34, Bohn’s Ed. %0a%3c %0a%3c 77 This is an exaggeration; Dioscorides says “ millet.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 78 Possibly the plant mentioned in B. xxv. c. 54; though the Aristo- %0a%3c lochia has not leaves like those of the myrtle. %0a%3c %0a%3c 79 Supposed to be identical with the Polygonos, mentioned above in c. 91. %0a%3c %0a%3c 80 See B. ix. c. 42, and B. xxvi. c. 11. From this passage it would %0a%3c %0a%3c appear that the maena was preserved in a somewhat similar way to our %0a%3c Sardines. 81 See B. xxvi. c. 11. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 106.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c THE RESEDA. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 265 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ciur. 105.— rhacoma: thirty-six remedies. %0a%3c %0a%3c Rhacoma 82 is imported from the regions situate beyond %0a%3c Pontus. 8 * The root of it is similar to black costus, 81 but %0a%3c smaller and somewhat redder, inodorous, and of a hot, astrin¬ %0a%3c gent flavour; when pounded, it yields a colour like that of %0a%3c wine, 6 * but inclining to saffron. Applied topically, it reduces %0a%3c abscesses and inflammations, and heals wounds: used with %0a%3c raisin wine, it allays defluxions of the eyes; with honey, ecchy- %0a%3c mosis; and with vinegar, livid marks upon the skin. Reduced %0a%3c to powder, it is sprinkled upon malignant ulcers, and is given %0a%3c internally for spitting of hlood, in doses of one drachma, in %0a%3c water. For dysentery and coeliac affections, if unattended %0a%3c with fever, it is administered in wine; but if there is fever, in %0a%3c water. It is pounded more easily when it has been steeped in %0a%3c water the night before. A decoction of it is given, in doses %0a%3c of two drachmae, for ruptures, convulsions, contusions, and falls %0a%3c with violence. %0a%3c %0a%3c In cases of pains in the chest, a little pepper and myrrh is %0a%3c added. When the stomach is deranged, it is taken in cold %0a%3c water; and the same in cases of chronic cough, purulent ex¬ %0a%3c pectorations, liver complaint, affections of the Bpleen, sciatica, %0a%3c diseases of the kidneys, asthma, and hardness of breathing. %0a%3c Pounded and taken in doses of three oboli, in raisin wine, or %0a%3c used in the form of a decoction, it cures irritations of the tra¬ %0a%3c chea : applied with vinegar, it acts as a detergent upon lichens. %0a%3c It is taken in drink, also, for flatulency, cold shiverings, chilly %0a%3c fevers, hiccup, gripiugs of the bowels, herpetic ulcerations, %0a%3c oppressions of the head, vertigo attended with melancholy, %0a%3c lassitude accompanied with pain, and convulsions. %0a%3c %0a%3c chap. 106.— the reseda: two remedies. %0a%3c %0a%3c In the vicinity of Arimiuum, there is a well-known plant %0a%3c called “ reseda r” 86 it disperses abscesses and all kinds of in¬ %0a%3c flammations. Those who employ it for these purposes, add %0a%3c %0a%3c bJ The reading of this word is very doubtful. It is generally supposed %0a%3c to be the Rheum Rhaponticum of Linnaeus, Pontic rhubarb. %0a%3c %0a%3c M The shores of the Euxine. %0a%3c %0a%3c 81 See B. xii. c. 25. %0a%3c %0a%3c K “Fulvum,” probably, “tawny-coloured,” not white, red, or black; %0a%3c see B. xiv. cc. 11, 18. %0a%3c %0a%3c w Possibly the Reseda alba of Linnaeus. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 266 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. [Book XXVii. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c the following words : “ Reseda, 1 " 7 allay this disease ! knowest %0a%3c thou not, knowest thou not, what chick it is that has tom up %0a%3c these roots ? Let it have nor head nor feet l” 88 This formula %0a%3c is repeated thrice, the party spitting on the ground each time. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 107. -THESTCECHAS: THREE REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The stoechas 89 grows only in the islands of that name. 90 It %0a%3c is an odoriferous plant, with leaves like those of hyssop, and %0a%3c of a bitter taste. Taken in drink, it promotes menstruation, %0a%3c and allays pains in the chest. It forms an ingredient, also, in %0a%3c • antidotes. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 108. -THE SOLANUM, BY THE GREEKS CALLED STRYCHNON : %0a%3c %0a%3c TWO REMEDIAL PROPERTIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25 %0a%3c %0a%3c The solanum, 91 according to Cornelius Celsus, 93 is called %0a%3c “strychnon ” by the Greeks; it is possessed of repercussive aud %0a%3c refrigerative properties. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 109. -SMYRNION : THIRTY-TWO REMEDIES. SINON : TWO %0a%3c %0a%3c REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Smymion 93 has a stem like that of parsley, but larger leaves, %0a%3c and growing principally about the youug shoots, which are %0a%3c numerous. From the midst of these shoots the leaves make %0a%3c their appearance, unctuous, and bending towards the ground. %0a%3c This plant has a medicinal smell, penetrating to a certain %0a%3c degree, and agreeable: the colour of it is a pale yellow, and %0a%3c the stems bear rounded umbels like those of dill, 94 with a %0a%3c round, black seed, which dries at the beginning of summer. %0a%3c The root, also, is odoriferous, of an acrid, pungent flavour, soft %0a%3c and juicy, black on the outer coat and pale within. The smell %0a%3c of it partakes very much of the nature of that of myrrh, to %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 87 “ Reseda, morbos reseda.” A pun upon the name of the plant, and %0a%3c the verb “resedo.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 88 Like the silly charm itself, “ neither head nor tail.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 89 See B. xxvi. c. 27. %0a%3c %0a%3c 90 The Stcechades. See B. iii. c. 11, and B. xxxii. c. 11. %0a%3c %0a%3c 91 See B. xxi. c. 105, and c. 44 of this Book. The black nightshade is %0a%3c neither astringent nor cooling, but a narcotic poison. %0a%3c %0a%3c 92 De Re Sled. ii. 33. %0a%3c %0a%3c 93 See B. xix. cc. 48, 62. It is generally identified with the Smyrnium %0a%3c perfoliatum of Linnaeus, the Perfoliated alexander. %0a%3c %0a%3c 94 “ Anethi” is a preferable reading to “ apii,” “parsley.” %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 110.] %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c TELEPHION. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 267 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c which, in fact, it owes its name : it grows in localities of a %0a%3c stony nature, or covered with humus. Its medicinal properties %0a%3c are warming and resolvent. %0a%3c %0a%3c The leaves and root are used as a diuretic and as an emmen- %0a%3c agogue ; the seed arrests diarrhoea; and the root, applied topi¬ %0a%3c cally, disperses abscesses and suppurations, provided they are %0a%3c not inveterate, and reduces indurated tumours. It is useful, %0a%3c also, for injuries inflicted by the phalangium and by serpents, %0a%3c taken in wine, with the addition of cachrys, 95 polium, 96 or me- %0a%3c lissophyllum ; 91 the dose, however, must be taken a little at a %0a%3c time only, for otherwise it acts as an emetic, a reason for which %0a%3c it is sometimes administered with rue. The seed or root is %0a%3c curative of cough, hardness of breathing, and diseases of the %0a%3c thoracic organs, spleen, kidneys, and bladder; the root, too, is %0a%3c used for ruptures and convulsions. This plant facilitates %0a%3c delivery, and brings away the afterbirth; it is also given, iu %0a%3c combination with crethmos, 98 in wine, for sciatica. It acts as a %0a%3c sudorific and carminative, for which reason it is used to disperse %0a%3c flatulency of the stomach ; it promotes, also, the cicatrization %0a%3c of wounds. %0a%3c %0a%3c A juice is extracted from the root, which is very useful for %0a%3c female complaints, and for affections of the thoracic organs %0a%3c and viscera, possessing, as it does, certain calorific, digestive, %0a%3c and detergent properties. The seed, in particular, is given in %0a%3c drink for dropsy, external applications being made of the %0a%3c juice, and emollient poultices applied of the dried rind of the %0a%3c root. It is used, also, as a seasoning for food, boiled meat in %0a%3c particular, with the addition of honied wine, oil, and garum." %0a%3c %0a%3c Sinon, 1 a plant with a flavour very like that of pepper, pro¬ %0a%3c motes the digestion, and is highly efficacious for pains in the %0a%3c stomach. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 110. -TELEPHION : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c Telephion 2 resembles purslain in the stem and leaves. From %0a%3c %0a%3c 95 See B. xxiv. c. 60. 96 See B. xxi. c. 21. %0a%3c %0a%3c 91 See B. xxi. c. 86. 93 See B. xxvi. c. 60. %0a%3c %0a%3c 99 “ Fish-sauce.” See B. ix. c. 30, and B. xxxi. c. 43. %0a%3c %0a%3c 1 Possibly the same plant as the Sison of Dioscorides, identified with %0a%3c the Sison amoraum of Linnaeus, Field hone-wort, or stone-parsley. %0a%3c %0a%3c 9 Identified by F£e with 