em should mention that he is taking them for diseases %0a%3c of the groin, for abscesses of all kinds, and for wounds, and %0a%3c that he should pluck them with one hand only. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 114. - THE TRACniNIA ! ONE PROPERTY. %0a%3c %0a%3c What sort of plant the trachinia 12 is, the authorities do not %0a%3c state. I think that the assurance given by Democritus must %0a%3c be false: for it would be nothing less than a prodigy, for a %0a%3c plant, attached as an amulet, to consume the spleen in so short %0a%3c u time as three days. %0a%3c %0a%3c CRAP. 115. —THE TRAGONIS OR TUAGION : FOUR REMEDIES. %0a%3c %0a%3c The tragonis, 13 or tragion, grows nowhere but in the mari¬ %0a%3c time districts of the Isle of Crete ; it resembles the juniper in %0a%3c %0a%3c 9 “ Peltarum specie.” The “ pelta ” was a small, light shield, of %0a%3c various forms, hut most commonly, perhaps, that of a crescent. %0a%3c %0a%3c lu From 6\du>, “ to break.” %0a%3c %0a%3c 11 “ Persian mustard.” The Lunaria annua of Linnaeus, the Annual %0a%3c moon-wort, honesty, or satin-flower, has been suggested by Sprengel, but %0a%3c its identity is very doubtful. %0a%3c %0a%3c u This plant is unknown. A rose of this name is mentioned in R. xxi. %0a%3c %0a%3c c. 10. %0a%3c %0a%3c 13 See B. xiii. c. 36. Fee suggests that it may possibly be a variety of %0a%3c the Pistacia lentiscus of Linnaeus, the Mustieh-tree, or lentisk. Desfon- %0a%3c taincs identifies it with the Hypericon hircinum. M. Fraas ( Synopsis , p. %0a%3c 18^) suggests the Origanum maru. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 270 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c flint’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c the seed, leaf, and branches. Its milky juice, which thickens %0a%3c in the form of a gum, or its seed, taken in drink, expels pointed %0a%3c weapons from the flesh. The plant, too, is pounded fresh and %0a%3c applied as a liniment with wine, or, dried and powdered, with %0a%3c honey. It increases the milk in nursing women, and is 