ffron-leaved goat’s beard. Though its properties are not inert, it %0a%3c is never used in medicine. %0a%3c %0a%3c 16 In B. xx. c. 3. %0a%3c %0a%3c 17 See B. xxv. c. 70. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ’ 6 * See c. 41 of this Book. %0a%3c 18 See B. xxv. c. 54. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c Chap. 120-] MALADIES PECULIAR TO VARIOUS NATIONS. 2/1 %0a%3c %0a%3c of any of those which have been mentioned by me ; with the %0a%3c exception, indeed, of the sphondyle, 19 a kind of creeping %0a%3c insect, 20 which infests them all. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 119. —HOW THE GREATEST EFFICACY IN PLANTS MAY BE %0a%3c ENSURED. %0a%3c %0a%3c It is also an undoubted truth, that the virtues and properties %0a%3c of all roots are more feebly developed, when the fruit has been %0a%3c allowed to ripen ; and that it is the same with the seed, when %0a%3c incisions have been previously made in the root, for the ex¬ %0a%3c traction of the juice. The efficacy, too, of all plants is impaired %0a%3c by making habitual use of them ; and these substances, if em¬ %0a%3c ployed daily, lose equally their good or bad properties, when %0a%3c required to be effectual. All plants, too, have more powerful %0a%3c properties, when grown in soils that are cold and exposed to %0a%3c the north-eastern blasts, or in dry localities. %0a%3c %0a%3c CHAP. 120. -MALADIES PECULIAR TO VARIOUS NATIONS. %0a%3c %0a%3c There are certain differences, also, by no means inconsider¬ %0a%3c able, in the predispositions of the various nations of the earth. %0a%3c I have been informed, for instance, that the people of Egypt, %0a%3c Arabia, Syria, and Cilicia, are subject to tapeworm and maw- %0a%3c worm, while those of Thracia and Phrygia, on the other hand, %0a%3c are totally exempt from them. This, however, is less sur¬ %0a%3c prising than the fact that, although Attica and Boeotia are %0a%3c adjoining territories, the Thebans are troubled with these %0a%3c inflictions, while among the people of Athens they are un¬ %0a%3c known. %0a%3c %0a%3c Considerations of this description lead me now to turn my %0a%3c attention to the nature of the animated beings themselves, and %0a%3c the medicinal properties which are inborn in them, the most %0a%3c assured remedies, perhaps, for all diseases. %0a%3c %0a%3c For Nature, in fact, that parent of all things, has produced no %0a%3c animated being for the purpose solely of eating ; she has willed %0a%3c that it should be born to satisfy the wants of others, and in %0a%3c its very vitals has implanted medicaments conducive to health. %0a%3c While she has implanted them in mute 21 and inanimate %0a%3c objects even, she has equally willed that these, the most in- %0a%3c %0a%3c 19 A kind of foetid beetle, Hardouin says. Probably an Aphis. %0a%3c %0a%3c 50 “ Serpentis." 21 See B. xxii. c. 3. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 272 %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c pliny’s natural history. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c [Book XXVII. %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c valuable aids of life, should be also derived from the life of %0a%3c another—a subject for contemplation, marvellous in the highest %0a%3c degree ! 21 , %0a%3c %0a%3c Summary. —Remedies, narratives, and observations, six hun¬ %0a%3c dred and two. %0a%3c %0a%3c Roman authors quoted. — Caius Valgius, 22 Pompeius Le- %0a%3c naeus, 23 Sextius Niger 24 who wrote in Greek, Julius Bassus" %0a%3c who wrote in Greek, Antonius Castor, 26 Cornelius Celsus.” %0a%3c %0a%3c Foreign* authors quoted. — Theophrastus, 29 Apollodorus,* %0a%3c Democritus, 30 Aristogiton, 31 Orpheus, 32 Pythagoras, 33 Mago/ 1 %0a%3c Menauder 35 who wrote the “ Biochresta,” Nicander. 39 %0a%3c %0a%3c Medical authors quoted. —Mnesitheus, 37 Timaristus, 38 Si. %0a%3c nius, 39 Hippocrates, 40 Chrysippus, 41 Diodes, 42 Ophelion, 43 Heru- %0a%3c clides, 44 Hicesius, 43 Dionysius, 46 Apollodorus 47 of Citium, Apol- %0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c 31 It is with regret that at the close of this Book, we take leave of %0a%3c the valuable Annotations of M. Fee, a series of illustrations which reflect %0a%3c the highest credit on 